<deck>
  <title>AP CSA Essential Knowledge</title>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two things define a type?</p></front>
    <back><p>A set of values (a domain) and a set of operations on them.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the definition of a type, what is the "domain"?</p></front>
    <back><p>The set of values that belong to that type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>int</code> considered a different type from <code>double</code>, even though both represent numbers?</p></front>
    <back><p>They have different domains (sets of possible values) and different operations defined on them.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If someone says "a type is just a set of values," what part of the definition are they missing?</p></front>
    <back><p>The set of operations defined on those values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to say that operations are part of a type's definition?</p></front>
    <back><p>A type is not just its values but also what you can do with them; the allowed operations are integral to what the type is.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two categories of data types in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Primitive types and reference types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>String</code> a primitive or reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code> is a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>int</code> a primitive or reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code> is a primitive type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do primitive and reference types differ in what a variable stores?</p></front>
    <back><p>A primitive variable stores the actual value directly, while a reference variable stores a reference to where the object lives in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a Java data type be something other than primitive or reference?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Every data type in Java is either a primitive type or a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three primitive data types used in AP CSA?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which primitive type represents logical values?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which primitive type would you use to store the number 3.14?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What do the three AP CSA primitive types represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>Numbers (<code>int</code> and <code>double</code>) and logical values (<code>boolean</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>char</code> one of the primitive types used in AP CSA?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The AP CSA course only uses <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the main reference types used in AP CSA?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>, arrays, <code>ArrayList</code>, and other classes we write ourselves, all of which extend <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What do all reference types in Java have in common regarding inheritance?</p></front>
    <back><p>They all extend <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is an array a primitive type or a reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p>An array is a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>ArrayList</code> extend <code>Object</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. All reference types, including <code>ArrayList</code>, extend <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you write your own class <code>Dog</code>, what type does it extend by default?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Object</code>. All classes extend <code>Object</code> either directly or indirectly.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which data types in Java have a syntax for writing literal values?</p></front>
    <back><p>The primitive types (<code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>) and <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a literal value in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A value written directly in the source code using the type's literal syntax, such as <code>1234</code>, <code>9.876</code>, <code>true</code>, or <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the literal syntax for a <code>String</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Text enclosed in double quotes, e.g. <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which of these is a <code>double</code> literal: <code>1234</code> or <code>9.876</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>9.876</code> is a <code>double</code> literal. <code>1234</code> is an <code>int</code> literal.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>ArrayList</code> have a literal syntax in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Only the primitive types and <code>String</code> have literal syntax.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many bytes of memory does an <code>int</code> use in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Four bytes (32 bits).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What constants represent the minimum and maximum values an <code>int</code> can hold?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> and <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't an <code>int</code> store arbitrarily large numbers?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because an <code>int</code> is stored in only 32 bits, limiting it to values from <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many bits are used to store an <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>32 bits.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the range of <code>int</code> inclusive or exclusive of <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> and <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Inclusive. An <code>int</code> can be exactly <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> or <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when an <code>int</code> expression evaluates to a value outside the <code>int</code> range?</p></front>
    <back><p>An overflow occurs, producing a mathematically incorrect <code>int</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1</code> evaluate to in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>, due to integer overflow.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does Java throw an exception when integer overflow occurs?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It silently produces a mathematically incorrect value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is integer overflow?</p></front>
    <back><p>When an <code>int</code> computation produces a value outside the representable range, wrapping around to a mathematically incorrect result.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you add 1 to the largest possible <code>int</code>, do you get a larger number?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You get <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>, which is a very large negative number, due to overflow.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What data type represents numbers with fractional parts in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many bits are used to store a <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>64 bits.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What three components does a <code>double</code> encode in its 64-bit representation?</p></front>
    <back><p>A significand, an exponent, and a sign.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is the storage of a <code>double</code> similar to scientific notation?</p></front>
    <back><p>Like scientific notation, a <code>double</code> encodes a significand (the digits), an exponent (the magnitude), and a sign (positive or negative).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which is larger in memory, an <code>int</code> or a <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>double</code> (64 bits) is twice the size of an <code>int</code> (32 bits).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the only two values of the <code>boolean</code> type?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of values does the <code>boolean</code> data type represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>Logical values: true and false.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you write the two <code>boolean</code> literal values in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code> (all lowercase).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>boolean</code> variable hold a value other than <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>boolean</code> has exactly two possible values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>boolean</code> a primitive or reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean</code> is a primitive type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do reference variables actually store?</p></front>
    <back><p>A reference (pointer) to where the real object value lives in memory, not the object itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When you pass a reference type to a method, what is actually passed?</p></front>
    <back><p>A copy of the reference to the object, not a copy of the object itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between what an <code>int</code> variable and a <code>String</code> variable store?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>int</code> variable stores the actual integer value; a <code>String</code> variable stores a reference to the <code>String</code> object in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When a method returns a reference type, what is actually returned?</p></front>
    <back><p>A reference to the object in memory, not a copy of the object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does comparing two reference variables with <code>==</code> sometimes give unexpected results?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>==</code> compares the references (memory addresses), not the actual object values. Two different objects with the same contents will have different references.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is <code>null</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A special reference value that represents "no object."</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default value of an uninitialized member variable of a reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>null</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What value do uninitialized elements of a <code>String[]</code> array contain?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>null</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can <code>null</code> be written as a literal value in Java code?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. You write it simply as <code>null</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can an <code>int</code> variable hold <code>null</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>null</code> is only valid for reference types, not primitives.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What exception is thrown when you call a method on a <code>null</code> reference?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>NullPointerException</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What causes a <code>NullPointerException</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Using the dot operator to call a method or access an instance variable on a <code>null</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you write <code>s.length()</code> when <code>s</code> is <code>null</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>NullPointerException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you access an instance variable on a <code>null</code> reference without getting an exception?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Using the dot operator on <code>null</code> for any purpose throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is a <code>NullPointerException</code> a compile-time error or a runtime error?</p></front>
    <back><p>A runtime error. The code compiles fine but fails when executed if the reference is <code>null</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the memory associated with a variable hold?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each variable has associated memory that is used to hold its value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a variable exist without any memory allocated to it?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Every variable has associated memory used to hold its value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between a variable and computer memory?</p></front>
    <back><p>A variable is associated with a region of memory that stores its current value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When you assign a value to a variable, where does that value go?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is stored in the memory associated with that variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If two variables hold different values, what does that imply about their memory?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each variable has its own associated memory, so they store their values independently.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the memory of a primitive-type variable hold compared to a reference-type variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>A primitive-type variable holds the actual value directly, while a reference-type variable holds a reference (pointer) to an object stored elsewhere in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you declare <code>int x = 5;</code>, is the value 5 stored directly in the variable's memory or somewhere else?</p></front>
    <back><p>Directly in the variable's memory, because <code>int</code> is a primitive type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When you declare <code>String s = "hello";</code>, what is actually stored in the memory of <code>s</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A reference to the <code>String</code> object, not the string data itself. The actual data is stored elsewhere in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can two reference variables point to the same object but two primitive variables cannot share the same memory location?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because reference variables store references (addresses) to objects elsewhere in memory, so multiple references can point to the same address. Primitive variables store actual values directly in their own memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens in memory when you assign one reference variable to another, e.g. <code>Dog b = a;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The reference stored in <code>a</code> is copied into <code>b</code>, so both variables now hold references to the same object. The object itself is not copied.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the minimum two things required in a variable declaration?</p></front>
    <back><p>A type and a name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which of the following is a valid minimal variable declaration: <code>x;</code>, <code>int;</code>, or <code>int x;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int x;</code> — a declaration must include both a type and a name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is an initial value required when declaring a variable in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A minimal declaration only requires a type and a name; initialization can happen later.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the syntax for the simplest possible variable declaration in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>type name;</code> — for example, <code>int count;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you write <code>double;</code> in Java, will it compile? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A variable declaration requires both a type and a name; <code>double;</code> is missing the name.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the type of a variable determine?</p></front>
    <back><p>It determines what kind of values can be assigned to the variable and what kind of value it produces when used as an expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a variable is declared as <code>int x;</code>, can you assign <code>x = "hello";</code>? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The type <code>int</code> restricts the variable to integer values, so assigning a <code>String</code> is a type error.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When you use a variable in an expression like <code>x + 1</code>, how does Java know the result type?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type of the variable determines the kind of value it produces when used as an expression, which Java uses to determine the result type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two things does a variable's type control?</p></front>
    <back><p>1) What values can be assigned to the variable, and 2) what type of value it produces when used in an expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why would <code>boolean b = 42;</code> fail to compile?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type <code>boolean</code> only allows <code>true</code> or <code>false</code> values; <code>42</code> is an <code>int</code> and violates the type constraint.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the purpose of a variable's name?</p></front>
    <back><p>It allows us to refer to the variable in assignment expressions and to use it as a value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the code <code>int score = 10; score = score + 5;</code>, how is the name <code>score</code> used?</p></front>
    <back><p>On the left of <code>=</code> it identifies the variable being assigned; on the right it refers to the variable's current value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you access a variable's value without knowing its name?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The name is what allows you to refer to the variable in assignments and as a value in expressions.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two ways a variable's name is used in code?</p></front>
    <back><p>1) In assignment expressions (to store a value), and 2) as a value (to retrieve the stored value).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>x = x * 2;</code>, does <code>x</code> serve the same role on both sides of the <code>=</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. On the right side, <code>x</code> refers to the variable's current value; on the left side, it identifies the variable to assign the result to.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when two reference variables point to the same object and you modify the object through one of them?</p></front>
    <back><p>The change is visible through both variables, since they both reference the same object in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Given <code>int[] a = {1,2}; int[] b = a; b[0] = 99;</code>, what is <code>a[0]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>99</code>. Both <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> reference the same array, so changes via <code>b</code> are visible through <code>a</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is aliasing (two variables referencing the same object) both useful and dangerous?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is useful because it avoids copying large objects, but dangerous because changes through one variable unexpectedly affect the other.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can two variables of a primitive type share the same underlying value in the way reference variables can share an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Primitive variables each hold their own independent copy of the value; there is no shared object to alias.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>Dog rover = new Dog(); Dog buddy = rover;</code>, how many <code>Dog</code> objects exist?</p></front>
    <back><p>One. Both <code>rover</code> and <code>buddy</code> hold references to the same <code>Dog</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>final</code> keyword do when applied to a variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>It prevents the variable's value from being changed once it has been initialized.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Will the following code compile? <code>final int x = 10; x = 20;</code></p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>x</code> is declared <code>final</code>, so reassigning it causes a compile-time error.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>final</code> variable holds a reference to an object, can the object's fields be modified?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. <code>final</code> prevents reassigning the reference, but the object it points to can still be mutated.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>final</code> variable be declared without an initial value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, but it must be assigned exactly once before it is used. After that single assignment, it cannot be changed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>final int x = 5;</code> and <code>int x = 5;</code> in terms of later usage?</p></front>
    <back><p>With <code>final</code>, any attempt to reassign <code>x</code> later will cause a compilation error. Without <code>final</code>, <code>x</code> can be reassigned freely.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two main kinds of variables in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Local variables and member variables. Member variables are further divided into instance variables and static variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two subcategories of member variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Instance variables (one per object) and static variables (one per class).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does an instance variable differ from a static variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>An instance variable belongs to a specific object (each object has its own copy), while a static variable belongs to the class and is shared among all instances.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is a local variable also considered a member variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Local variables are declared inside methods or constructors, while member variables are declared at the class level.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Into how many total categories can Java variables be classified?</p></front>
    <back><p>Three: local variables, instance (member) variables, and static (member) variables.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where are local variables declared?</p></front>
    <back><p>In the body of methods and constructors.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a local variable be used outside the method in which it is declared?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Local variables may only be used within the method or constructor where they are declared.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a local variable be declared <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Local variables are not accessible outside their method or constructor, so access modifiers do not apply to them.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why don't local variables need access modifiers like <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because they are not accessible at all outside the method or constructor in which they are declared, making access modifiers unnecessary.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the scope of a local variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>The method or constructor body in which it is declared. It cannot be accessed from anywhere else.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Are method parameters considered local variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Parameters declared in a method or constructor are also local variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method parameter be accessed from another method?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Like all local variables, parameters are only accessible within the method or constructor where they are declared.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>public void greet(String name)</code>, what kind of variable is <code>name</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A local variable. Parameters are a form of local variable scoped to the method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do parameters differ from other local variables in terms of initialization?</p></front>
    <back><p>Parameters are automatically initialized with the argument values passed by the caller, whereas other local variables must be explicitly initialized before use.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a constructor declares a parameter <code>int size</code>, is <code>size</code> a local or member variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>A local variable. Constructor parameters are local variables, just like method parameters.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is "shadowing" in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>When a local variable has the same name as a member variable, the name refers to the local variable, hiding (shadowing) the member variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a class has a field <code>int x</code> and a method declares <code>int x</code>, which <code>x</code> does the method body refer to?</p></front>
    <back><p>The local variable <code>x</code>. It shadows the member variable of the same name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does shadowing remove or destroy the member variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The member variable still exists; it is simply hidden by the local variable within that scope.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which variable takes precedence when a local variable and a member variable share the same name?</p></front>
    <back><p>The local variable takes precedence within the method or constructor where it is declared.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is shadowing often considered bad practice?</p></front>
    <back><p>It can cause confusion because the name refers to the local variable rather than the member variable, potentially leading to bugs when the programmer intends to use the member variable.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you access a shadowed instance variable from within a method?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>this.</code> followed by the variable name, e.g. <code>this.x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you access a shadowed static member variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use the class name followed by a dot, e.g. <code>ClassName.SOME_VARIABLE</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>this.name</code> refer to when <code>name</code> is both a parameter and an instance field?</p></front>
    <back><p>The instance field, not the parameter. The <code>this.</code> prefix explicitly refers to the current object's member variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use <code>this.</code> to access a static variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Technically Java allows it, but it is bad practice. Static variables should be accessed with <code>ClassName.</code> to make clear they belong to the class, not an instance.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a constructor <code>public Dog(String name) { this.name = name; }</code>, why is <code>this.</code> necessary?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the parameter <code>name</code> shadows the instance field <code>name</code>. Without <code>this.</code>, both sides of the assignment would refer to the parameter.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: An expression is any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an expression in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression is any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What distinguishes an expression from a statement in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression can be evaluated to produce a value, whereas a statement does not necessarily produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: Every expression in Java produces a value when evaluated.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. By definition, an expression is a part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which of these is an expression: <code>int x = 5;</code> or <code>x + 5</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x + 5</code> is an expression because it evaluates to a value. <code>int x = 5;</code> is a declaration statement.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is a <code>void</code> method call not considered an expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because a <code>void</code> method does not return a value, and an expression must evaluate to produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Literal values evaluate to the value they denote -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does a literal value expression like <code>10</code> or <code>"foo"</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>A literal value evaluates to the value it denotes: <code>10</code> evaluates to the integer 10 and <code>"foo"</code> evaluates to the string "foo".</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Give three examples of literal value expressions in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p>Examples: <code>10</code> (int literal), <code>3.14</code> (double literal), <code>"hello"</code> (String literal).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>"foo"</code> an expression? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. <code>"foo"</code> is a literal value expression that evaluates to the String value "foo".</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the simplest kind of expression in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A literal value, such as <code>10</code>, <code>true</code>, or <code>"hello"</code>, which directly denotes the value it evaluates to.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How does Java determine what value the expression <code>42</code> produces?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>42</code> is a literal, so it evaluates directly to the integer value 42 without any computation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Variables evaluate to the current value of the variable -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does a variable expression like <code>x</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to the current value stored in the variable <code>x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>5</code> and then we set <code>x = 10</code>, what does the expression <code>x</code> evaluate to afterward?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to <code>10</code>, the current value of <code>x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> an expression? What does it evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. <code>Math.PI</code> is a variable expression that evaluates to the current value of <code>PI</code>, approximately 3.141592653589793.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How does a variable expression differ from a literal expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>A literal always evaluates to the same fixed value, while a variable expression evaluates to whatever value is currently stored in the variable, which can change over time.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you use a variable as an expression before it has been assigned a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>The compiler reports an error because the variable may not have been initialized. Local variables must be assigned before use.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Method calls to non-void methods evaluate to the returned value -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the expression <code>s.substring(1)</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to the value returned by calling the <code>substring</code> method on <code>s</code> with argument <code>1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why can non-<code>void</code> method calls be used as expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because they return a value, and an expression is anything that evaluates to produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can a call to a <code>void</code> method be used as an expression? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A <code>void</code> method does not return a value, so it cannot be used where a value is needed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to the <code>double</code> value returned by the <code>sqrt</code> method, approximately 1.4142135623730951.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In the expression <code>s.substring(1).length()</code>, how many method call expressions are there?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two: <code>s.substring(1)</code> is one method call expression, and <code>.length()</code> called on its result is the second.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Object instantiations via new evaluate to a reference to a newly created object -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the expression <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to a reference to a newly created <code>ArrayList</code> object that has been initialized by its constructor.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What two things happen when the <code>new</code> keyword is used to create an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>A new object is created in memory and the appropriate constructor is run to initialize it. The expression evaluates to a reference to that object.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>new String("hello")</code> an expression? What does it produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It produces a reference to a newly created <code>String</code> object initialized with the value "hello".</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the role of the constructor when <code>new</code> is used?</p></front>
    <back><p>The constructor initializes the newly created object before the reference to it is returned as the value of the expression.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does the <code>new</code> expression return the object itself or a reference to it?</p></front>
    <back><p>It returns a reference to the newly created object, not the object itself.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Array access expressions evaluate to the value at the given position -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the expression <code>xs[0]</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to the value stored at index 0 in the array <code>xs</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>int[] nums = {10, 20, 30}</code>, what does <code>nums[2]</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to <code>30</code>, the value stored at index 2.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of expression is <code>arr[i]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is an array access expression that evaluates to the value stored at position <code>i</code> in the array <code>arr</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you use an array access expression with an index that is out of bounds?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can an array access expression appear on the left side of an assignment? What about as a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes to both. On the left side it designates a storage location; as an expression it evaluates to the value stored at that position.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Compound expressions made up of expressions and operators -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a compound expression in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A compound expression is made up of sub-expressions combined with operators, e.g. <code>x + 2</code>, and evaluates to a value determined by the operator and its operands.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In the compound expression <code>x + 2</code>, what are the sub-expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x</code> (a variable expression) and <code>2</code> (a literal expression) are the sub-expressions.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What determines the value of a compound expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>The operator and the values of its operands determine the value of a compound expression.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a compound expression that contains another compound expression.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>(x + 2) * 3</code> is a compound expression where <code>x + 2</code> is itself a compound sub-expression.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>a &gt; b &amp;&amp; c &lt; d</code> a compound expression? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It combines multiple sub-expressions (<code>a &gt; b</code> and <code>c &lt; d</code>) with the <code>&amp;&amp;</code> operator to produce a boolean value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Each expression has a type determined by sub-expressions and operators -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How is the type of an expression determined in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type is determined by the types of its sub-expressions and the operators involved.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the type of an expression describe?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type describes the kind of values the expression can produce.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is an <code>int</code>, what is the type of the expression <code>x + 2</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>, because the <code>+</code> operator applied to two <code>int</code> operands produces an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is an <code>int</code>, what is the type of <code>x + 2.0</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>, because an arithmetic operation involving at least one <code>double</code> produces a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it important that every expression in Java has a type?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type allows the compiler to check that expressions are used correctly and that values are compatible with where they are used.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Anywhere a value of a given type is needed we can use any expression of that type -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you pass an expression like <code>x + 1</code> as an argument to a method that expects an <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Anywhere a value of a given type is needed, you can use any expression that produces a value of that type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What principle allows you to write <code>System.out.println(2 + 3)</code> instead of storing the result in a variable first?</p></front>
    <back><p>Anywhere a value of a given type is needed, any expression that produces that type can be used, so <code>2 + 3</code> can appear directly as an argument.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a method parameter requires a <code>String</code>, can you pass <code>s.substring(0, 3)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because <code>s.substring(0, 3)</code> is an expression that produces a <code>String</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why can expressions be nested inside other expressions in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because anywhere a value of a given type is needed, any expression producing that type can be substituted, allowing expressions to be composed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a variable is declared as <code>double d</code>, which expressions can be assigned to it?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any expression that produces a <code>double</code> value (or an <code>int</code>, which is automatically promoted to <code>double</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Arithmetic expressions produce int and double values -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What types of values do arithmetic expressions produce in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Arithmetic expressions produce <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an arithmetic expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression that produces an <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> value using arithmetic operators.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>"hello" + "world"</code> an arithmetic expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It produces a <code>String</code>, not an <code>int</code> or <code>double</code>. It is a string concatenation expression.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: An arithmetic expression in Java can produce a <code>float</code> value.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. In the AP CSA context, arithmetic expressions produce <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which two numeric types are relevant for arithmetic expressions on the AP CSA exam?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code> and <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The arithmetic operators are +, -, *, /, and % -->

  <card>
    <front><p>List all five arithmetic operators in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>+</code> (addition), <code>-</code> (subtraction), <code>*</code> (multiplication), <code>/</code> (division), and <code>%</code> (modulus/remainder).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>%</code> operator do in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It returns the remainder after dividing the left operand by the right operand.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>10 % 3</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>1</code>, because 10 divided by 3 has a remainder of 1.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which arithmetic operator can be used to determine if a number is even or odd?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>%</code> (modulus) operator. If <code>n % 2 == 0</code>, the number is even.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Are there any exponentiation operators among the five Java arithmetic operators?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The five arithmetic operators are <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>. For exponentiation, use <code>Math.pow()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: An arithmetic operation on two ints evaluates to an int -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the type of the result when you add two <code>int</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p>The result is an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>7 / 2</code> evaluate to in Java, and why?</p></front>
    <back><p>It evaluates to <code>3</code> because both operands are <code>int</code>s, so integer division is performed and the fractional part is discarded.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does <code>5 / 3</code> produce <code>1</code> rather than <code>1.666...</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because an arithmetic operation on two <code>int</code>s evaluates to an <code>int</code>, and integer division truncates the fractional part.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>3 * 4</code> and what is its type?</p></front>
    <back><p>The result is <code>12</code> and its type is <code>int</code>, because both operands are <code>int</code>s.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If both <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are <code>int</code> variables, what is the type of <code>a % b</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>, because an arithmetic operation on two <code>int</code>s always produces an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: An arithmetic operation with at least one double evaluates to a double -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the type of <code>7 / 2.0</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>, because at least one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>7 / 2.0</code> evaluate to, and how does it differ from <code>7 / 2</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>7 / 2.0</code> evaluates to <code>3.5</code> (a <code>double</code>), while <code>7 / 2</code> evaluates to <code>3</code> (an <code>int</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is an <code>int</code> and <code>y</code> is a <code>double</code>, what is the type of <code>x + y</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>, because any arithmetic operation with at least one <code>double</code> produces a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How can you force the division <code>a / b</code> (both <code>int</code>s) to produce a <code>double</code> result?</p></front>
    <back><p>Cast one operand to <code>double</code>, e.g. <code>(double) a / b</code>, so that at least one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: <code>3 + 4.0</code> produces an <code>int</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. It produces a <code>double</code> (value <code>7.0</code>) because one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Operators can be used to construct compound expressions -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How are compound arithmetic expressions formed?</p></front>
    <back><p>By combining simpler expressions with arithmetic operators, e.g. <code>x + y * 2</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>(a + b) * (c - d)</code> a compound expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It is formed by combining multiple sub-expressions with operators.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can the result of one arithmetic operation be used as an operand in another?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Operators can be used to construct compound expressions where sub-expressions serve as operands.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What makes <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> a compound expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>It contains multiple operators (<code>+</code> and <code>*</code>) combining three sub-expressions into a single expression.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many operators are in the compound expression <code>a * b + c / d - e</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Three: <code>*</code>, <code>+</code> (or <code>/</code>), and <code>-</code>. There are actually three operators: <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, <code>+</code>, and <code>-</code> — that is four operators.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Operands are associated with operators according to operator precedence -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What determines how operands are grouped with operators during evaluation?</p></front>
    <back><p>Operator precedence determines how operands are associated with operators.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> evaluate to, and why?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>14</code>, because <code>*</code> has higher precedence than <code>+</code>, so <code>3 * 4</code> is evaluated first.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How can you override operator precedence in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>By using parentheses. For example, <code>(2 + 3) * 4</code> evaluates to <code>20</code> instead of <code>14</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which operators have higher precedence: <code>+</code> and <code>-</code>, or <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code> have higher precedence than <code>+</code> and <code>-</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>10 - 2 * 3</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>4</code>, because <code>2 * 3</code> is evaluated first (higher precedence), then subtracted from <code>10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Dividing an integer by zero results in an ArithmeticException -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you divide an integer by zero in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>10 / 0</code> produce in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It throws an <code>ArithmeticException</code> because integer division by zero is not allowed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does dividing a <code>double</code> by zero also throw an <code>ArithmeticException</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Dividing a <code>double</code> by zero produces <code>Infinity</code> or <code>NaN</code>, not an exception. Only integer division by zero throws an <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>ArithmeticException</code> a compile-time error or a runtime error?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a runtime error (exception). The code compiles successfully but throws the exception when executed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>7 % 0</code> produce in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code>, because the modulus operator also requires a non-zero divisor for integer operands.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The casting operators (int) and (double) produce numeric values of the specified type -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What do the casting operators <code>(int)</code> and <code>(double)</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>They produce numeric values of the specified type from the given operand.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>(int) 3.9</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>3</code>, because casting a <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> truncates the fractional part.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>(double) 5</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>5.0</code>, a <code>double</code> with the same mathematical value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is casting in Java an expression? Does it produce a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A cast like <code>(int) 3.7</code> is an expression that evaluates to a value of the target type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you convert a <code>double</code> variable <code>d</code> to an <code>int</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use the casting operator: <code>(int) d</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Casting double to int truncates the fractional part -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the fractional part when you cast a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The fractional part (digits to the right of the decimal point) is truncated (removed).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>(int) 9.99</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>9</code>, because casting truncates the fractional part rather than rounding.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does casting <code>(int) -3.7</code> round down to <code>-4</code> or truncate to <code>-3</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It truncates to <code>-3</code>. Casting removes the fractional part, it does not round toward negative infinity.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between truncation and rounding when casting <code>double</code> to <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Truncation simply drops the decimal portion (e.g. 3.9 becomes 3), while rounding would go to the nearest integer (e.g. 3.9 becomes 4). Java casting truncates.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>(int) 0.999</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code>, because the fractional part is truncated.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Casting int to double produces the same mathematical value -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What does casting an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>double</code> with the same mathematical value, since all <code>int</code> values are exactly representable as <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is any precision lost when casting an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. All <code>int</code> values can be exactly represented as <code>double</code> values, so no precision is lost.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>(double) 42</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>42.0</code>, a <code>double</code> with the same mathematical value as the <code>int</code> 42.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is casting from <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> considered a "widening" conversion?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>double</code> can represent all <code>int</code> values and more, so no information is lost when converting to the wider type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Compare the safety of casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> versus <code>double</code> to <code>int</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>Casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> is safe (no data loss). Casting <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> can lose data because the fractional part is truncated.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Using an int where a double is expected causes automatic conversion -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you use an <code>int</code> value where a <code>double</code> is expected?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>int</code> value is automatically converted to a <code>double</code> value without requiring an explicit cast.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a method parameter is <code>double x</code>, can you pass an <code>int</code> value? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Java automatically converts the <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> when an <code>int</code> is used where a <code>double</code> is expected.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is automatic type promotion in the context of <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>When an <code>int</code> is used where a <code>double</code> is expected, Java automatically converts it to a <code>double</code> without an explicit cast.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does Java automatically convert a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code> when an <code>int</code> is expected?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. That would be a narrowing conversion that loses data, so an explicit cast is required.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does <code>double d = 5;</code> compile without error?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the <code>int</code> value <code>5</code> is automatically converted to the <code>double</code> value <code>5.0</code> when used where a <code>double</code> is expected.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Rounding doubles to int using (int)(x + 0.5) or (int)(x - 0.5) -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How can you round a positive <code>double</code> value <code>x</code> to the nearest <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code>. Adding 0.5 before truncating effectively rounds to the nearest integer.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you round a negative <code>double</code> value to the nearest <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>(int)(x - 0.5)</code> for negative numbers.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>(int)(3.7 + 0.5)</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>4</code>, because <code>3.7 + 0.5 = 4.2</code>, and <code>(int) 4.2</code> truncates to <code>4</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>(int)(3.2 + 0.5)</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>3</code>, because <code>3.2 + 0.5 = 3.7</code>, and <code>(int) 3.7</code> truncates to <code>3</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the rounding trick <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code> work for positive numbers?</p></front>
    <back><p>Adding 0.5 pushes values at or above the midpoint (e.g. 3.5) up to the next integer before truncation, while values below the midpoint (e.g. 3.4) stay below and truncate down.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a boolean expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any expression that results in a <code>boolean</code> value. The values used in the expression may be <code>boolean</code>s or other types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>x &gt; 10</code> a boolean expression even though <code>x</code> is a number? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A boolean expression is defined by its result type, not the types of its operands. <code>x &gt; 10</code> evaluates to a <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What type does the expression <code>a == b</code> always evaluate to, regardless of the types of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It always evaluates to a <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a boolean expression contain values that are not themselves <code>boolean</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. For example, <code>x &gt; 10</code> uses numeric values but is still a boolean expression because it produces a <code>boolean</code> result.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What makes an expression a "boolean expression" rather than some other kind of expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>It produces a <code>boolean</code> value as its result, regardless of the types of its operands.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the four sources from which boolean expressions can be constructed?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean</code> literals, <code>boolean</code> variables, methods that return <code>boolean</code>, and expressions involving logical, equality, or relational operators.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a boolean expression built from a <code>boolean</code> literal.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code> or <code>false</code> used directly in an expression, e.g. <code>true &amp;&amp; x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which three categories of operators can appear in boolean expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p>Logical operators, equality operators, and relational operators.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Besides operators and literals, what other two things can be used to build boolean expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean</code> variables and methods that return <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method returns <code>boolean</code>, can a call to that method be used as part of a boolean expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Methods that return <code>boolean</code> are one of the building blocks of boolean expressions.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do logical operators operate on and what do they produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>They operate on <code>boolean</code> values and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do logical operators differ from relational operators in terms of their operand types?</p></front>
    <back><p>Logical operators take <code>boolean</code> operands; relational operators take numeric operands. Both produce a <code>boolean</code> result.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to use a logical operator on a non-boolean value in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It causes a compile-time error. Logical operators require <code>boolean</code> operands.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result type of applying <code>!</code> to a <code>boolean</code> value?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>boolean</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you apply <code>&amp;&amp;</code> to two <code>int</code> values in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Logical operators like <code>&amp;&amp;</code> only operate on <code>boolean</code> values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three logical operators in Java and their names?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!</code> (not), <code>&amp;&amp;</code> (and), and <code>||</code> (or).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which Java logical operator is unary (takes only one operand)?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!</code> (not). It takes a single <code>boolean</code> operand and negates it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>||</code> operator do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It performs a logical OR: it returns <code>true</code> if at least one of its two <code>boolean</code> operands is <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>&amp;&amp;</code> operator do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It performs a logical AND: it returns <code>true</code> only if both of its <code>boolean</code> operands are <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many logical operators does Java have and what symbols represent them?</p></front>
    <back><p>Three: <code>!</code>, <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, and <code>||</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the precedence order of the three logical operators from highest to lowest?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!</code> (highest), then <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, then <code>||</code> (lowest).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the expression <code>!a || b &amp;&amp; c</code>, which operator is evaluated first?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!</code> is evaluated first (highest precedence), then <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, then <code>||</code>. It is equivalent to <code>(!a) || (b &amp;&amp; c)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>&amp;&amp;</code> said to be analogous to multiplication and <code>||</code> to addition?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>true &amp;&amp; x</code> equals <code>x</code> (like <code>1 * x = x</code>) and <code>false || x</code> equals <code>x</code> (like <code>0 + x = x</code>). Multiplication has higher precedence than addition, just as <code>&amp;&amp;</code> has higher precedence than <code>||</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>&amp;&amp;</code> have higher or lower precedence than <code>||</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Higher. <code>&amp;&amp;</code> binds more tightly than <code>||</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does the precedence of <code>!</code> compare to <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!</code> has the highest precedence of all three logical operators, binding before both <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is short-circuit evaluation?</p></front>
    <back><p>When the result of a <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code> expression can be determined from the first operand alone, the second operand is not evaluated.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>false &amp;&amp; someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Because the left side is <code>false</code>, the <code>&amp;&amp;</code> result must be <code>false</code> regardless, so the second operand is short-circuited.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is short-circuit evaluation useful in <code>s.length() &gt;= 3 &amp;&amp; s.substring(0, 3).equals("abc")</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>If the string is shorter than 3 characters, the left side is <code>false</code> and the <code>substring</code> call is skipped, preventing a runtime exception.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>true || someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Because the left side is <code>true</code>, the <code>||</code> result must be <code>true</code>, so the second operand is not evaluated.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which two logical operators support short-circuit evaluation?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>. The <code>!</code> operator has only one operand so short-circuiting does not apply.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do De Morgan's Laws allow you to do with boolean expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p>Transform some boolean expressions into equivalent expressions by distributing or factoring out negation across <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>According to De Morgan's Laws, what is <code>!(a || b)</code> equivalent to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!a &amp;&amp; !b</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>According to De Morgan's Laws, what is <code>!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> equivalent to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!a || !b</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Rewrite <code>!x &amp;&amp; !y</code> using De Morgan's Laws.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!(x || y)</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Rewrite <code>!x || !y</code> using De Morgan's Laws.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>!(x &amp;&amp; y)</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a boolean identity?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two different boolean expressions that evaluate to the same value for all possible combinations of their variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can truth tables be used with boolean expressions?</p></front>
    <back><p>To prove boolean identities by showing that two expressions produce the same result for every possible combination of variable values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give a trivial example of a boolean identity.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> is equivalent to <code>a</code>. They evaluate to the same value for all possible values of <code>a</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you use a truth table to verify that <code>!a &amp;&amp; !b</code> equals <code>!(a || b)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>List all four combinations of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> (<code>true</code>/<code>true</code>, <code>true</code>/<code>false</code>, <code>false</code>/<code>true</code>, <code>false</code>/<code>false</code>), compute both expressions for each, and verify they match in every row.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a more complex example of a boolean identity beyond <code>a &amp;&amp; true == a</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>De Morgan's Laws, e.g. <code>!a &amp;&amp; !b</code> is equivalent to <code>!(a || b)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which operators can be used to compare both primitive and reference values for equality?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>==</code> and <code>!=</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use <code>==</code> to compare two <code>int</code> values? Two object references?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes to both. <code>==</code> and <code>!=</code> work on both primitive and reference values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>==</code> and <code>!=</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>==</code> returns <code>true</code> if the operands are equal; <code>!=</code> returns <code>true</code> if they are not equal. They are complementary.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many equality operators does Java have and what are they?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two: <code>==</code> (equal to) and <code>!=</code> (not equal to).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do the equality operators work differently on primitives vs. references?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. For primitives they compare values; for references they compare whether both refer to the same object (or are both <code>null</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When are two object references <code>==</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only when they both reference the exact same object in memory, or when they are both <code>null</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If two <code>String</code> objects contain the same characters, are they necessarily <code>==</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>==</code> checks whether they are the same object, not whether their contents match.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that <code>==</code> on references may not match the notion of "the same" you care about?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two different objects can be logically equivalent (same content) but not <code>==</code> because they are distinct objects in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are two <code>null</code> references considered <code>==</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. If both references are <code>null</code>, <code>==</code> returns <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the only way two non-null object references can be <code>==</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>They must both point to the exact same object in memory.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the <code>equals</code> method come from and what is its purpose?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is inherited from <code>Object</code> and is often overridden by classes to determine if two instances are logically equivalent.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>==</code> and <code>.equals()</code> for two <code>String</code> objects with identical content?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>==</code> may return <code>false</code> if they are different objects, but <code>.equals()</code> returns <code>true</code> because <code>String</code> overrides <code>equals</code> to compare character content.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>equals</code> an operator in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It is a method that returns a <code>boolean</code>, not an operator.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do classes override the <code>equals</code> method inherited from <code>Object</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>To provide a meaningful notion of equivalence based on the object's data, rather than the default identity comparison.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do all Java classes have an <code>equals</code> method, even if they don't explicitly define one?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Every class inherits <code>equals</code> from <code>Object</code>. The default implementation uses reference identity (same as <code>==</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>==</code> sometimes pronounced "equals equals"?</p></front>
    <back><p>To distinguish the <code>==</code> operator from the <code>equals</code> method, since both relate to equality but work differently.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What confusion does the name "equals equals" help avoid?</p></front>
    <back><p>It prevents confusion between the <code>==</code> operator (which compares references for objects) and the <code>.equals()</code> method (which compares logical equivalence).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If someone says "use equals to compare those strings," should you use <code>==</code> or <code>.equals()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>.equals()</code>. The term "equals" alone typically refers to the method. The operator is distinguished as "equals equals" (<code>==</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many equal signs make up the equality operator in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two: <code>==</code>. A single <code>=</code> is the assignment operator.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the risk of confusing <code>=</code> with <code>==</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>=</code> is assignment, not comparison. Using <code>=</code> where <code>==</code> is intended will cause a compilation error or unintended behavior.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do relational operators operate on and what do they produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>They operate on numeric values and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use relational operators to compare two <code>String</code> objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Relational operators (<code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;=</code>, <code>&gt;=</code>) only work on numeric values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do relational operators differ from equality operators in terms of what types they accept?</p></front>
    <back><p>Relational operators only accept numeric values, while equality operators (<code>==</code>, <code>!=</code>) accept both primitive and reference values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result type of a relational operator expression like <code>5 &gt; 3</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>boolean</code> value (in this case, <code>true</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can relational operators be used to compare <code>boolean</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Relational operators operate on numeric values only.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the four relational operators in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>&lt;</code> (less than), <code>&gt;</code> (greater than), <code>&lt;=</code> (less than or equal to), and <code>&gt;=</code> (greater than or equal to).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>10 &lt; 20</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code>, because 10 is less than 20.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>&lt;</code> is true only when the left operand is strictly less than the right. <code>&lt;=</code> is also true when they are equal.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>5 &gt;= 5</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code>, because 5 is equal to 5 and <code>&gt;=</code> includes equality.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which side of a relational operator is compared to which? For example, in <code>a &lt; b</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>The left-hand operand (<code>a</code>) is compared to the right-hand operand (<code>b</code>). <code>a &lt; b</code> is <code>true</code> if <code>a</code> is less than <code>b</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't you write <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Java does not allow chaining relational operators. The expression would be parsed as <code>(0 &lt;= x) &lt; 10</code>, comparing a <code>boolean</code> to an <code>int</code>, which is a type error.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you express the mathematical range <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Combine two relational expressions with <code>&amp;&amp;</code>: <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What operator is used to combine two relational expressions when checking a range?</p></front>
    <back><p>The logical AND operator <code>&amp;&amp;</code>. For example: <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What would happen if you tried to compile <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>You would get a compile error because <code>0 &lt;= x</code> evaluates to a <code>boolean</code>, and you cannot use <code>&lt;</code> to compare a <code>boolean</code> with <code>10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does Java differ from math notation when expressing that a value is within a range?</p></front>
    <back><p>In math you can chain comparisons like <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code>, but in Java you must split it into two comparisons joined by <code>&amp;&amp;</code>: <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In Java, is an assignment like <code>x = 5</code> a statement or an expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is technically an expression that produces a value, but we normally care more about its side effect of changing the value of the variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What side effect does an assignment expression have in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It changes the value stored in the variable or array element being assigned to.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What value does the expression <code>x = 7</code> produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>It produces the value <code>7</code> (the value that was assigned).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it possible to write <code>a = b = 0</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because assignments are expressions that produce a value. <code>b = 0</code> assigns <code>0</code> to <code>b</code> and evaluates to <code>0</code>, which is then assigned to <code>a</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If assignment in Java is an expression, why do we usually treat it as if it were a statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because we normally care about its side effect (changing a variable's value) rather than the value the expression produces.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the only assignable places (lvalues) in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Variables (local or member) and array access expressions, e.g. <code>x</code>, <code>obj.someField</code>, and <code>nums[0]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you assign a value to the result of a method call like <code>getX() = 5</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Only variables and array elements are assignable; method return values are not.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>nums[0] = 42</code> a valid assignment in Java? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because array access expressions are one of the assignable places in Java.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give three examples of assignable places in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x</code> (local variable), <code>obj.someField</code> (member variable), and <code>nums[0]</code> (array element).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between a local variable and a member variable in terms of assignability?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both are assignable places in Java. A local variable is declared inside a method, while a member variable (field) belongs to an object or class.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the assignment operator <code>=</code> do in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It stores the value of the expression on the right side in the variable or array element referenced on the left side.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the <code>=</code> operator be used both to initialize and to change a variable's value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The assignment operator <code>=</code> allows a program to both initialize and change the value stored in a variable or array element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>int x = 10;</code>, which side of <code>=</code> is evaluated first?</p></front>
    <back><p>The expression on the right side is evaluated first, and the resulting value is then stored in the variable on the left.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What value does the assignment expression <code>y = 3 + 4</code> produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>It produces <code>7</code>, the value that was assigned to <code>y</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you write <code>nums[2] = 99</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The value <code>99</code> is stored in element at index 2 of the array <code>nums</code>, and the expression evaluates to <code>99</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>List the five compound assignment operators in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>+=</code>, <code>-=</code>, <code>*=</code>, <code>/=</code>, <code>%=</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is <code>x += 2</code> equivalent to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x = x + 2</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What value does a compound assignment expression like <code>x *= 3</code> produce?</p></front>
    <back><p>The new value of <code>x</code> after the multiplication.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can compound assignment operators be used on array elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Compound assignment operators can be used to assign a new value to a variable or array element computed from the old value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>10</code>, what is the value of <code>x</code> and the expression after <code>x -= 3</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both the value of <code>x</code> and the value of the expression are <code>7</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do the <code>++</code> and <code>--</code> operators do in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>They add 1 or subtract 1 from the value of a variable or array element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is <code>x++</code> equivalent to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x += 1</code> or <code>x = x + 1</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>5</code>, what value does the expression <code>x++</code> produce?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>5</code>. The postfix <code>++</code> operator returns the value <em>before</em> incrementing, so <code>x</code> becomes <code>6</code> but the expression evaluates to <code>5</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the <code>++</code> and <code>--</code> operators be used on array elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. They can be used on variables and array elements, e.g. <code>nums[0]++</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between postfix <code>x++</code> and prefix <code>++x</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both increment <code>x</code> by 1, but <code>x++</code> evaluates to the value before incrementing, while <code>++x</code> evaluates to the new value after incrementing.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>=</code> is the assignment operator (assigns a value), while <code>==</code> is the equality comparison operator (tests whether two values are equal).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What can happen if you accidentally use <code>=</code> instead of <code>==</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>You may get compiler errors or incorrect and confusing behavior from your program.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many equals signs does the assignment operator use? How many does the equality operator use?</p></front>
    <back><p>The assignment operator uses one (<code>=</code>); the equality comparison operator uses two (<code>==</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is mixing up <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> a common source of bugs?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because they look similar but have completely different purposes: one assigns a value, the other compares values. Using the wrong one can cause confusing behavior.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>if (x = 5)</code>, is this an assignment or a comparison?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is an assignment, not a comparison. The comparison would be <code>if (x == 5)</code>. In Java this will usually cause a compiler error unless <code>x</code> is a <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is procedural abstraction?</p></front>
    <back><p>Hiding how a value is computed or how an effect is achieved, allowing a programmer to use a method without knowing exactly how it is written.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is procedural abstraction useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>It allows programmers to use methods without needing to know the implementation details, making code easier to use and reason about.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does procedural abstraction hide from the programmer?</p></front>
    <back><p>How a value is computed or how an effect is achieved.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does procedural abstraction relate to methods in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Methods are the mechanism for procedural abstraction in Java; they encapsulate implementation details behind a callable interface.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of using procedural abstraction when calling <code>Math.sqrt(25)</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>You can call <code>Math.sqrt(25)</code> to get <code>5.0</code> without knowing how the square root is calculated internally.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the unit of procedural abstraction in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In Java, what construct lets you encapsulate a computation behind a name?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is the method considered the unit of procedural abstraction?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because it is the smallest construct in Java that bundles a sequence of operations behind a single callable name, hiding implementation details.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the equivalent of a "function" or "procedure" in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method. In Java, the method is the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can procedural abstraction in Java be achieved without methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. In Java, the method is the unit of procedural abstraction; it is the primary mechanism for hiding how computations are performed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to "decompose" a problem using methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>Breaking down a large problem into smaller sub-problems by writing methods that each solve a specific sub-problem, with methods calling other methods as needed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do methods help manage complexity in a program?</p></front>
    <back><p>They allow us to decompose a large problem into smaller, more manageable sub-problems, each handled by its own method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between decomposition and method calls?</p></front>
    <back><p>Decomposition is achieved by writing methods that call other methods, with each method solving a portion of the overall problem.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why would you split a large method into several smaller methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>To decompose the problem into smaller sub-problems, making the code easier to understand, test, and maintain.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What programming principle is demonstrated when a method calls other helper methods to solve parts of a task?</p></front>
    <back><p>Decomposition -- breaking a large problem into smaller sub-problems solved by individual methods.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a method provided by Java that you can use without writing it yourself.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.sqrt</code> -- it computes the square root of a number and is provided by Java's <code>Math</code> class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are two sources of methods a Java programmer can use?</p></front>
    <back><p>Methods provided by Java (such as <code>Math.sqrt</code>) and methods that the programmer writes themselves.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you always have to write your own methods in Java, or are some provided for you?</p></front>
    <back><p>Java provides many built-in methods (e.g., the <code>Math</code> methods), so you do not always need to write your own.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What class provides methods like <code>sqrt</code> and <code>abs</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>Math</code> class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it useful that Java provides pre-written methods like <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>So programmers can use them without having to implement the algorithms themselves, saving time and reducing errors.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need to know how a method is implemented in order to use it?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You can use methods without knowing exactly how they are implemented.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why might you write your own method to hide details even though you wrote the implementation?</p></front>
    <back><p>To hide details in one part of your code so that other parts don't need to deal with those details, improving organization and readability.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What benefit does hiding implementation details in a method provide?</p></front>
    <back><p>Other code can use the method without needing to understand the details, making the program easier to work with.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is it only useful to hide details when using someone else's methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It is also useful to hide details in your own methods so that other parts of your code don't need to deal with those details.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does using methods you wrote yourself relate to procedural abstraction?</p></front>
    <back><p>Even self-written methods provide procedural abstraction by hiding implementation details from the code that calls them.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that methods allow us to build "layers of abstraction"?</p></front>
    <back><p>Code in one method can call other methods, which can call still other methods, creating multiple layers where each layer hides the details of the layer below.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method call other methods in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The code in one method can call other methods, allowing us to build layers of abstraction.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do layers of abstraction help in programming?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each layer hides the complexity of the layers below it, so programmers can work at a higher level without worrying about low-level details.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of how methods calling other methods creates layers of abstraction.</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>printReport()</code> method might call <code>formatData()</code>, which calls <code>calculateTotal()</code>. Each method hides details from the one above it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between calling methods from other methods and abstraction?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each method call adds a layer of abstraction by hiding the details of how a sub-task is accomplished.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What three things must a method signature specify in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The return type, the name of the method, and the method's parameters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a method signature?</p></front>
    <back><p>The part of a method declaration that specifies the return type, method name, and parameters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>public int add(int a, int b)</code>, identify the three parts of the method signature.</p></front>
    <back><p>Return type: <code>int</code>. Name: <code>add</code>. Parameters: <code>int a</code> and <code>int b</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method in Java omit its return type?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The method signature must specify a return type; use <code>void</code> if the method does not return a value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you declare a method without specifying its parameters?</p></front>
    <back><p>The method must still include an empty parameter list with parentheses, e.g. <code>void doSomething()</code>. Parameters are part of the method signature.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>void</code> return type mean in a method signature?</p></front>
    <back><p>It indicates that the method does not return any value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Must a non-<code>void</code> method return a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. All non-<code>void</code> methods must return a value of the type specified in the method signature.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if a method with return type <code>int</code> does not include a <code>return</code> statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>The code will not compile. Non-<code>void</code> methods must return a value of the specified type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method with return type <code>double</code> return an <code>int</code> value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because <code>int</code> is automatically widened to <code>double</code>. The return value must be compatible with the declared return type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the return type in a method signature tell you about how the method can be used?</p></front>
    <back><p>It specifies the kind of value the method produces, which determines how the method call can be used in expressions.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a <code>void</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method with <code>void</code> as its return type, called only for its effects (such as printing or changing object state), not for a return value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give two examples of effects a <code>void</code> method might have.</p></front>
    <back><p>Printing to the screen and changing the state of an object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use the result of a <code>void</code> method in an expression like <code>int x = doSomething()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A <code>void</code> method does not return a value, so it cannot be used as part of an expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why would you call a <code>void</code> method if it doesn't return a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>For its side effects, such as printing output, modifying an object's state, or writing to a file.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>System.out.println()</code> an example of a <code>void</code> method? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It is called for its effect (printing to the screen) and does not return a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How must method parameters be specified in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each parameter must be specified with a type and a name, since parameters are variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are method parameters considered variables in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Method parameters are variables and must be declared with both a type and a name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is wrong with <code>public void greet(name)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The parameter <code>name</code> is missing its type. It should be something like <code>public void greet(String name)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you declare a method parameter without giving it a name?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Parameters must have both a type and a name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>public double power(double base, int exp)</code>, how many parameters are there and what are their types?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two parameters: <code>base</code> of type <code>double</code> and <code>exp</code> of type <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you write a method that takes no arguments in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>With an empty parameter list consisting of just a pair of parentheses, e.g. <code>public int getValue()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What goes between the parentheses of a method that takes no arguments?</p></front>
    <back><p>Nothing. The parameter list is empty, e.g. <code>doSomething()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>public void reset()</code> a valid method declaration?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Methods that take no arguments are written with an empty parameter list (just parentheses).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you omit the parentheses entirely if a method takes no parameters?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Even methods with no parameters must include the empty parentheses, e.g. <code>getName()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What distinguishes a method with no parameters from a field access in Java syntax?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method call always includes parentheses (e.g., <code>obj.getName()</code>), while a field access does not (e.g., <code>obj.name</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What encloses the body of a method in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>A pair of curly braces <code>{}</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the method body appear relative to the method signature?</p></front>
    <back><p>The body follows the signature and is enclosed in curly braces <code>{}</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is contained inside a method's curly braces?</p></front>
    <back><p>The method body -- the statements and expressions that execute when the method is called.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the opening brace <code>{</code> part of the method signature or the method body?</p></front>
    <back><p>It marks the beginning of the method body, not part of the signature.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you omit the curly braces around a method body?</p></front>
    <back><p>The code will not compile. Method bodies must be enclosed in <code>{}</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What variables can code within a method body refer to?</p></front>
    <back><p>Parameters from the signature, local variables declared in the method, <code>static</code> variables of the class, and (in instance methods) instance variables and <code>this</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the keyword <code>this</code> refer to inside an instance method?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object on which the method was invoked.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can code in a <code>static</code> method refer to instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Only instance methods can refer to instance variables and <code>this</code>. Static methods can only access static variables, parameters, and local variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method body access <code>static</code> variables declared in its class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Code within a method body can refer to any <code>static</code> variables declared in the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between what a <code>static</code> method and an instance method can access?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both can access parameters, local variables, and static variables. Instance methods can additionally access instance variables and the special variable <code>this</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does a method call consist of syntactically?</p></front>
    <back><p>A reference to the method and a possibly empty argument list of comma-separated expressions, e.g. <code>foo(10, "some string")</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the call <code>foo(10, "hello")</code>, what are <code>10</code> and <code>"hello"</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are the arguments -- expressions in the argument list that are evaluated and passed to the method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How are multiple arguments separated in a Java method call?</p></front>
    <back><p>With commas, forming a comma-separated list of expressions.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method call have an empty argument list?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A method call can have a possibly empty argument list, e.g. <code>doSomething()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the argument list in a method call?</p></front>
    <back><p>A comma-separated list of expressions enclosed in parentheses that provides values to the method's parameters.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the expressions in a method call's argument list before the method runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are evaluated to get values, which are then used to initialize the corresponding parameters in the method signature.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How are arguments matched to parameters in a method call?</p></front>
    <back><p>By position: the first parameter gets the value of the first argument, the second parameter gets the second argument, and so on.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method is declared as <code>void print(String msg, int count)</code>, and called as <code>print("hi", 3)</code>, what values do the parameters receive?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>msg</code> receives <code>"hi"</code> and <code>count</code> receives <code>3</code>, matched by position.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are arguments evaluated before or after the method starts executing?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before. The argument expressions are evaluated first, then the method runs with its parameters initialized to those values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between an argument and a parameter?</p></front>
    <back><p>An argument is the value passed in a method call. A parameter is the variable declared in the method signature that receives that value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Must the arguments passed to a method be compatible with the parameter types?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The arguments must be compatible with the types identified in the parameter list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you pass a <code>String</code> to a method that expects an <code>int</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The code will not compile because the argument type is not compatible with the parameter type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does this rule about type compatibility apply to constructors as well as methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Arguments passed to both constructors and method calls must be compatible with the parameter types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you pass an <code>int</code> to a parameter of type <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because <code>int</code> is automatically widened to <code>double</code>, making it type-compatible.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does "type compatible" mean for method arguments?</p></front>
    <back><p>The argument's type must either match the parameter's type exactly or be automatically convertible to it (e.g., <code>int</code> to <code>double</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How are arguments passed to methods in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>By copying values (pass by value). The method receives a copy of each argument's value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method change the value of a local variable in the calling method?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Because arguments are passed by copying values, a method cannot change the value of a local variable in the method that called it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is "pass by value"?</p></front>
    <back><p>A mechanism where arguments are passed to methods by copying the values, so the method works with copies rather than the original variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you pass <code>int x = 5</code> to a method that sets its parameter to <code>10</code>, what is <code>x</code> after the call?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>x</code> is still <code>5</code>. Java passes by value, so the method only changed its local copy.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't a Java method implement a "swap" that changes two variables in the caller?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because Java passes arguments by value (copying), so changes to the parameters inside the method do not affect the caller's variables.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a reference to a mutable object is passed to a method, can the method alter the object's state?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The reference is copied, but both copies point to the same object, so the method can use the reference to alter the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can a method modify an object passed to it even though Java uses pass by value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the value of a reference type is the reference itself. The copied reference still points to the same object, so the method can mutate it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you pass an <code>ArrayList</code> to a method and the method calls <code>add()</code> on it, will the caller see the change?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The method has a copy of the reference that points to the same <code>ArrayList</code> object, so changes to the list are visible to the caller.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>As a matter of good practice, when should a method modify a mutable object passed as an argument?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only when doing so is an inherent part of the method's purpose. Methods should not modify mutable objects passed as arguments unnecessarily.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between changing a parameter variable and changing the object it refers to?</p></front>
    <back><p>Changing the parameter variable (reassigning it) only affects the local copy. Changing the object it refers to (calling mutator methods) affects the actual object seen by all code holding a reference to it.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the flow of control when a method is called?</p></front>
    <back><p>It jumps to the start of the method (after initializing parameters). When the method returns, flow of control returns to the point where the method was called.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does any code execute in a method after a <code>return</code> statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. No code executes in a method after a <code>return</code> statement.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the parameters when a method starts executing?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are initialized to the values of the corresponding arguments before the method body begins executing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After a method returns, where does execution continue?</p></front>
    <back><p>At the point in the calling method where the method was called.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the sequence of events when <code>int result = add(3, 4);</code> executes?</p></front>
    <back><p>Arguments <code>3</code> and <code>4</code> are evaluated, flow jumps to <code>add</code>, parameters are initialized, the body executes, a value is returned, and flow returns to assign the result to <code>result</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How is a value returned from a method in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Using a <code>return</code> statement: the keyword <code>return</code> followed by an expression that evaluates to a value of the correct type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What must follow the <code>return</code> keyword in a non-<code>void</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression that evaluates to a value of the method's declared return type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>return</code> used in a <code>void</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p>With no following expression, simply as <code>return;</code>, to exit the method early. It is optional since <code>void</code> methods return automatically at the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>void</code> method use a <code>return</code> statement with a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. In a <code>void</code> method, <code>return</code> can only be used without a following expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if a non-<code>void</code> method tries to <code>return</code> a value of the wrong type?</p></front>
    <back><p>The code will not compile. The return expression must evaluate to a value compatible with the declared return type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is the value returned by a method the original value or a copy?</p></front>
    <back><p>A copy. The value returned by a method is copied, just like method arguments.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method returns a reference to an object, can the caller modify that object?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A reference returned by a method can be used to modify the object it references, since the copy is of the reference, not the object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is the copying of return values similar to the copying of arguments?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both are passed by value. Primitive values are fully copied; reference values are copied as references, so the same object can be accessed through the copy.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method returns a reference to an internal <code>ArrayList</code>, what risk does this create?</p></front>
    <back><p>The caller can use the returned reference to modify the internal list, potentially breaking the object's state. This is why return values are copies of the reference, not copies of the object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does returning a primitive value from a method allow the caller to change the method's local variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The returned value is a copy, so changes by the caller do not affect the method's local variable (which no longer exists after the method returns).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is a call to a non-<code>void</code> method an expression in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A method call to a non-<code>void</code> method is a kind of expression whose value is the value returned by the method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can you write <code>int x = Math.abs(-5);</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>Math.abs(-5)</code> is a non-<code>void</code> method call, which is an expression that evaluates to the returned value (<code>5</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use a non-<code>void</code> method call as an argument to another method?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because a non-<code>void</code> method call is an expression that produces a value, e.g. <code>System.out.println(Math.max(3, 7))</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What determines the type of the expression <code>someMethod()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The return type declared in the method's signature.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a non-<code>void</code> method call appear anywhere an expression of its return type can appear?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Since it is an expression of that type, it can be used in assignments, as arguments, in arithmetic, etc.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can a call to a <code>void</code> method be used as part of an expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A <code>void</code> method does not return a value, so it can only be called for its effect and cannot be part of an expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do <code>void</code> methods typically need a <code>return</code> statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. They simply return when execution reaches the end of the method body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>int x = System.out.println("hi");</code> invalid?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>println</code> is a <code>void</code> method that does not return a value, so it cannot be used as an expression in an assignment.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the purpose of calling a <code>void</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p>For its side effects, such as printing output or modifying object state. It does not produce a value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a <code>void</code> method return if it has no <code>return</code> statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>It returns automatically when execution reaches the closing brace <code>}</code> at the end of the method body.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Within a class, can a <code>static</code> method call an instance method directly by name?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A <code>static</code> method cannot call an instance method without an explicit object to invoke it on, because there is no implicit <code>this</code> in a <code>static</code> context.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a non-<code>static</code> method, what does calling another method by its simple name (without a dot) actually mean?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is equivalent to calling the method on <code>this</code>, i.e. on the same object the current method was invoked on.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can non-<code>static</code> methods reference other methods in the same class by name alone, but <code>static</code> methods cannot always do so?</p></front>
    <back><p>Non-<code>static</code> methods have an implicit <code>this</code> reference, so a simple method name is equivalent to <code>this.methodName()</code>. <code>static</code> methods have no <code>this</code>, so they can only call other <code>static</code> methods by name; calling an instance method requires an explicit object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to call an instance method from a <code>static</code> method without specifying an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>You get a compile-time error because there is no implicit object (<code>this</code>) available in a <code>static</code> context to invoke the instance method on.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If method <code>foo()</code> and method <code>bar()</code> are both instance methods in the same class, and <code>foo()</code> calls <code>bar()</code>, on which object is <code>bar()</code> invoked?</p></front>
    <back><p>On <code>this</code> -- the same object that <code>foo()</code> was invoked on.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you typically invoke a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Using the class name, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the expression <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>, what does <code>Math</code> refer to and why is it used instead of an object?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math</code> is the class name. Because <code>sqrt</code> is a <code>static</code> method, it belongs to the class itself, not to any instance, so it is referenced via the class name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the general syntax pattern for calling a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ClassName.methodName(arguments)</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why don't you need to create an object to call <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>sqrt</code> is a <code>static</code> method, so it is associated with the <code>Math</code> class itself, not with any particular instance of it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare how you call a <code>static</code> method vs. an instance method from outside their class.</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>static</code> method is called on the class name (e.g. <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>), while an instance method is called on an object reference (e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you invoke an instance method on an object of another class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Using an expression that evaluates to a reference to the object, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the expression <code>s.substring(1)</code>, what must <code>s</code> be?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>s</code> must be an expression that evaluates to a reference to an object (in this case a <code>String</code>) on which the <code>substring</code> method can be invoked.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to call an instance method using the class name (e.g. <code>String.substring(1)</code>) instead of an object reference?</p></front>
    <back><p>You get a compile-time error because instance methods require an object to be invoked on, not a class name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three parts of the syntax for calling an instance method on another object?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression evaluating to an object reference, the dot operator, and the method name with arguments.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Could you write <code>(x + y).toString()</code> to call an instance method? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>Not with primitive types, since they are not objects. But if <code>x + y</code> produces an object reference, then yes -- any expression that evaluates to an object reference can be used before the dot operator.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are control constructs and what two kinds do they fall into?</p></front>
    <back><p>Control constructs allow us to control the flow of execution beyond calling and returning from methods. They fall into conditional control constructs and looping control constructs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Without control constructs, how does execution flow through a program?</p></front>
    <back><p>Execution flows sequentially from one statement to the next, with control transferring only via method calls and returns.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Name the two categories of control constructs in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p>Conditional control constructs (e.g. <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>) and looping control constructs (e.g. <code>while</code>, <code>for</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do control constructs differ from method calls as a way to change the flow of execution?</p></front>
    <back><p>Method calls transfer control to another method and then return. Control constructs change the flow within a method by conditionally executing or repeating statements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What problem would a program have if it had no control constructs at all?</p></front>
    <back><p>Every statement would execute exactly once in sequence (aside from method calls and returns), so the program could not make decisions or repeat actions.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do conditional statements do to the normal flow of control?</p></front>
    <back><p>They interrupt the normal sequential flow by allowing some code to execute or not depending on the value of a <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What type of expression does a conditional statement evaluate to decide which code runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>boolean</code> expression, which evaluates to either <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Without conditional statements, how would the statements in a block of code execute?</p></front>
    <back><p>They would all execute in sequential order, every time, with no ability to skip any statements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the key idea behind conditional control constructs?</p></front>
    <back><p>They make the execution of a set of statements depend on whether a <code>boolean</code> condition is <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a conditional statement cause code to execute more than once?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Conditional statements only decide whether code executes or not. Repeating code requires looping constructs.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of selection does a simple <code>if</code> statement provide?</p></front>
    <back><p>A one-way selection: a set of statements either is or is not executed, depending on whether the <code>boolean</code> condition is <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when the condition of a simple <code>if</code> statement evaluates to <code>false</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The body of the <code>if</code> is skipped entirely and execution continues with the next statement after the <code>if</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a simple <code>if</code> statement, under what condition is the body executed?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only when the <code>boolean</code> condition evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is a simple <code>if</code> called a "one-way selection"?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because there is only one possible action: execute the body or skip it. There is no alternative branch when the condition is <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare a one-way selection (<code>if</code>) with a two-way selection (<code>if</code>/<code>else</code>). What is the key difference?</p></front>
    <back><p>A one-way selection either executes a block or skips it. A two-way selection always executes exactly one of two blocks, choosing based on the condition.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statement provide that a simple <code>if</code> does not?</p></front>
    <back><p>A two-way selection: one set of statements executes when the condition is <code>true</code>, and a different set executes when it is <code>false</code>. Exactly one branch always runs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, is it possible for neither branch to execute?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Exactly one of the two branches always executes: the <code>if</code> body when the condition is <code>true</code>, the <code>else</code> body when it is <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When the <code>boolean</code> condition in an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> is <code>false</code>, which code runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>The statements in the <code>else</code> block.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a two-way selection differ from a one-way selection in terms of guaranteed execution?</p></front>
    <back><p>In a two-way selection, exactly one of two code blocks is guaranteed to execute. In a one-way selection, the block may or may not execute.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the general structure of a two-way selection in Java.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>if (condition) { /* runs when true */ } else { /* runs when false */ }</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How is a multi-way selection written in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>With an <code>if</code>, one or more <code>else if</code> clauses, and optionally a final <code>else</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain, which body gets executed?</p></front>
    <back><p>The body of the first <code>if</code> or <code>else if</code> whose condition is <code>true</code>, or the <code>else</code> body if all conditions are <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens in a multi-way selection if none of the conditions are <code>true</code> and there is no <code>else</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No body executes; execution continues past the entire <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code> chain.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a multi-way selection, can more than one branch execute?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Only the body of the first condition that evaluates to <code>true</code> executes. The remaining branches are skipped.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the order of conditions matter in an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code> chain?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the first condition that evaluates to <code>true</code> determines which body runs. If conditions overlap, a different order could produce different behavior.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you place an <code>if</code> statement inside the body of another <code>if</code> statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Any code can go in the body of an <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>, including other conditional statements, producing nested conditional statements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a nested conditional statement?</p></front>
    <back><p>A conditional statement (such as an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>) that appears inside the body of another conditional statement.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What kinds of statements can appear in the body of an <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any code at all, including other <code>if</code>, <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, and <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> statements, loops, method calls, etc.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What scenario might require a nested <code>if</code> inside another <code>if</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>When a second decision only needs to be made if the first condition is <code>true</code>, such as checking a sub-condition that only applies in certain cases.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is there a limit to how deeply <code>if</code> statements can be nested?</p></front>
    <back><p>There is no language-imposed limit. However, deeply nested conditionals reduce readability and are often better expressed as multi-way selections or extracted methods.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> statement really, in terms of basic <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is just a regular <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> with a nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> in the <code>else</code> branch, written in a chained style for readability.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do we write <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chains instead of deeply nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements?</p></front>
    <back><p>To express a multi-way selection more clearly and readably, even though they are technically nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements under the hood.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> statements a separate language feature from <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. They are syntactically just nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements, but written in a chained format for clarity.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How could you rewrite <code>if (a) { ... } else if (b) { ... } else { ... }</code> using only simple <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>if (a) { ... } else { if (b) { ... } else { ... } }</code> -- the <code>else if</code> is just an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> nested inside the outer <code>else</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is chaining <code>else if</code> preferable to nesting <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> blocks?</p></front>
    <back><p>When expressing a multi-way selection among several alternatives, since chaining keeps the code flat and easier to read than deeply indented nesting.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do looping control constructs do?</p></front>
    <back><p>They change the normal flow of control by repeating a sequence of statements zero or more times.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is another name for looping control constructs?</p></front>
    <back><p>Iteration constructs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a loop body execute zero times?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Looping constructs repeat statements <em>zero</em> or more times, so it is possible for the body to never execute.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do looping constructs differ from conditional constructs in their effect on control flow?</p></front>
    <back><p>Conditional constructs choose whether to execute a block once or skip it. Looping constructs can repeat a block multiple times.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the minimum number of times a loop body can execute in a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Zero times, if the condition is <code>false</code> on the very first evaluation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When is the <code>boolean</code> expression in a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop evaluated?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before each iteration of the loop body, including the first iteration.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when the <code>boolean</code> expression in a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop evaluates to <code>true</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The loop body is executed, then the process repeats (the condition is evaluated again).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What causes a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop to stop iterating?</p></front>
    <back><p>The loop stops when its <code>boolean</code> expression evaluates to <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the condition in a <code>for</code> loop checked after the body executes or before?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before. The condition is evaluated before each iteration, including the first.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare when the loop condition is evaluated in <code>while</code> and <code>for</code> loops.</p></front>
    <back><p>In both <code>while</code> and <code>for</code> loops, the <code>boolean</code> expression is evaluated before each iteration, including the first. They behave the same in this regard.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if the <code>boolean</code> expression of a loop is <code>false</code> the very first time it is evaluated?</p></front>
    <back><p>The loop body is not executed at all.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is an infinite loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A loop whose <code>boolean</code> expression always evaluates to <code>true</code>, so the loop never stops on its own.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Under what condition does a <code>while</code> loop become an infinite loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>When the <code>boolean</code> expression never evaluates to <code>false</code>, so the loop repeats indefinitely.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between a loop that executes zero times and an infinite loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are opposite extremes: a zero-iteration loop has a condition that is <code>false</code> immediately, while an infinite loop has a condition that is never <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>for</code> loop execute zero times? Give an example.</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. For example, <code>for (int i = 0; i < 0; i++)</code> -- the condition is <code>false</code> on the first check, so the body never runs.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two parts of a <code>while</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition and the body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does a <code>while</code> loop have an initialization clause like a <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A <code>while</code> loop consists of only the condition and the body. Any initialization must happen before the loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a <code>while</code> loop differ structurally from a <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>while</code> loop has just a condition and a body, while a <code>for</code> loop adds an initialization clause and an update clause in its header.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the general structure of a <code>while</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>while (condition) { body }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>while</code> loop needs to initialize a counter, where does that code go?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before the <code>while</code> loop, since the loop itself only has a condition and a body.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Describe the execution sequence of a <code>while</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition is evaluated. If <code>true</code>, the body executes and the process repeats from the condition. If <code>false</code>, the loop ends.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After the body of a <code>while</code> loop executes, what happens next?</p></front>
    <back><p>Execution returns to the condition, which is evaluated again to decide whether to run the body once more or exit the loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the first thing that happens when a <code>while</code> loop is reached during execution?</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition is evaluated. If it is <code>true</code>, the body executes; if <code>false</code>, the loop is skipped entirely.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a <code>while</code> loop, how many times is the condition evaluated compared to the number of times the body runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition is evaluated one more time than the body runs, because the final evaluation (which yields <code>false</code>) does not lead to a body execution.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between the condition being checked and the body being executed in a <code>while</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition is checked first; only if it is <code>true</code> does the body execute. The condition acts as a gatekeeper for each iteration.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why do <code>while</code> loop conditions typically reference variables defined before the loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the condition needs to depend on values that can change, and the body needs to modify those values so the condition can eventually become <code>false</code> and the loop can terminate.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What must be true about the loop body for a <code>while</code> loop to eventually terminate?</p></front>
    <back><p>The body must change the values of one or more variables that the condition depends on, so that the condition eventually becomes <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if the body of a <code>while</code> loop never changes any variables that the condition depends on?</p></front>
    <back><p>If the condition was initially <code>true</code>, it remains <code>true</code> forever, resulting in an infinite loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a <code>while</code> loop, where are the variables typically defined that both the condition and the body reference?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before the loop, so they are in scope for both the condition and the body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Explain the relationship between the condition and the body of a <code>while</code> loop for correct termination.</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition checks variable values, and the body modifies those variables. This interplay allows the condition to eventually become <code>false</code>, ending the loop.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When are <code>while</code> loops most useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>When you do not know before the loop starts exactly how many times it needs to run.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Would you use a <code>while</code> loop or a <code>for</code> loop to read input until the user types "quit"? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>while</code> loop, because you don't know in advance how many inputs the user will provide before typing "quit."</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why might a <code>for</code> loop be less natural than a <code>while</code> loop when the number of iterations is unknown?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>for</code> loop's header is designed to declare, test, and update a loop variable with a known range. When the number of iterations is unknown, the <code>while</code> loop's simpler structure is a better fit.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example scenario where a <code>while</code> loop is more appropriate than a <code>for</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p>Searching for a value in a stream of unknown length, where you stop as soon as you find it or reach the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>while</code> loop be used when you know the number of iterations in advance?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, it can, but a <code>for</code> loop is typically preferred in that case because its header clearly expresses the initialization, condition, and update.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the two main parts of a <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A header and a body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does the structure of a <code>for</code> loop differ from a <code>while</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>for</code> loop has a header (with initialization, condition, and update) plus a body, while a <code>while</code> loop has only a condition and a body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What information does the header of a <code>for</code> loop convey that a <code>while</code> loop does not express in its syntax?</p></front>
    <back><p>The initialization of the loop variable and how the loop variable is updated after each iteration.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What separates the header from the body in a <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>The header is enclosed in parentheses after the keyword <code>for</code>, and the body follows, typically enclosed in curly braces.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What advantage does a <code>for</code> loop's header provide over a <code>while</code> loop's structure?</p></front>
    <back><p>It groups the initialization, condition, and update in one place, making the loop's control logic easier to see at a glance.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three parts of a <code>for</code> loop header, and how are they separated?</p></front>
    <back><p>The initialization clause, the condition, and the update clause, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What character separates the three parts of a <code>for</code> loop header?</p></front>
    <back><p>Semicolons.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)</code>, identify the initialization, condition, and update.</p></front>
    <back><p>Initialization: <code>int i = 0</code>; condition: <code>i < 10</code>; update: <code>i++</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are the three parts of a <code>for</code> loop header separated by commas or semicolons?</p></front>
    <back><p>Semicolons.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many semicolons appear inside the parentheses of a <code>for</code> loop header?</p></front>
    <back><p>Exactly two, separating the three parts: initialization, condition, and update.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When does the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop run?</p></front>
    <back><p>Once, before anything else in the loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop typically do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It declares and initializes a loop variable (e.g. <code>int i = 0</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many times does the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop execute?</p></front>
    <back><p>Exactly once.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop declare a new variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It typically declares and initializes the loop variable, such as <code>int i = 0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a variable is declared in the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop, what is its scope?</p></front>
    <back><p>The variable is scoped to the <code>for</code> loop -- it can be used in the condition, update, and body, but not outside the loop.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When is the condition of a <code>for</code> loop evaluated?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before each iteration of the loop. The loop only continues if the condition evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What usually appears in the condition of a <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>An expression involving the loop variable, such as <code>i < 10</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if the condition of a <code>for</code> loop is <code>false</code> on the first evaluation?</p></front>
    <back><p>The body never executes and the loop terminates immediately.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the condition of a <code>for</code> loop have to involve the loop variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>It usually does, but technically it can be any <code>boolean</code> expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the condition in a <code>for</code> loop evaluated before or after the update clause?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before. The sequence is: update (from previous iteration), then condition, then body.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When does the update clause of a <code>for</code> loop run?</p></front>
    <back><p>After the body of the loop executes and just before the next evaluation of the condition.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the update clause of a <code>for</code> loop typically do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It updates the loop variable, typically by incrementing or decrementing it (e.g. <code>i++</code> or <code>i--</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the update clause run before or after the loop body?</p></front>
    <back><p>After the body. The execution order is: body, then update, then condition check for the next iteration.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the complete execution order of a single iteration of a <code>for</code> loop (after initialization)?</p></front>
    <back><p>Condition is checked; if <code>true</code>, the body runs, then the update clause runs, then the cycle repeats at the condition.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the update clause run on the very first iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>Not before the first iteration. It runs after the body executes for the first time, before the condition is checked for the second iteration.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When is the body of a <code>for</code> loop executed relative to the condition and update?</p></front>
    <back><p>After the condition evaluates to <code>true</code> and before the update clause runs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can code in the body of a <code>for</code> loop access the loop variable declared in the header?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The loop variable declared in the header is in scope within the body.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) { System.out.println(i); }</code>, what is the full execution order for the first iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>Initialize <code>i = 0</code>, check <code>i < 5</code> (true), execute body (print 0), then run update <code>i++</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the body of a <code>for</code> loop modify the loop variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, though it is generally not recommended as it can make the loop harder to understand and may cause unexpected behavior.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After a <code>for</code> loop ends, can you use the loop variable declared in the header?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. A variable declared in the <code>for</code> loop header goes out of scope when the loop ends.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When are <code>for</code> loops typically used?</p></front>
    <back><p>When we know before the loop starts how many times we want to iterate, e.g. once for every character in a string or element of an array.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a situation where a <code>for</code> loop is preferred over a <code>while</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p>Iterating over every character in a string: <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++)</code>, since the number of iterations is known in advance.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is a <code>for</code> loop a good choice for iterating over an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the number of iterations (the array length) is known before the loop starts, and the <code>for</code> header cleanly expresses the init, condition, and update.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare when to use a <code>for</code> loop vs. a <code>while</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p>Use a <code>for</code> loop when the number of iterations is known in advance. Use a <code>while</code> loop when you don't know how many times to iterate.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Would you use a <code>for</code> loop or a <code>while</code> loop to iterate through all elements of an array? Why?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>for</code> loop, because the array length is known before the loop starts, making it a natural fit for the <code>for</code> loop's structure.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can a <code>for</code> loop be rewritten as a <code>while</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Any <code>for</code> loop can be rewritten as an equivalent <code>while</code> loop and vice versa.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When converting a <code>for</code> loop to a <code>while</code> loop, where does the initialization clause go?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before the <code>while</code> loop, since the <code>while</code> loop has no initialization clause of its own.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When converting a <code>for</code> loop to a <code>while</code> loop, where does the update clause go?</p></front>
    <back><p>Inside the body of the <code>while</code> loop, typically at the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Rewrite <code>for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) { body }</code> as an equivalent <code>while</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int i = 0; while (i < n) { body; i++; }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What structural difference exists between a <code>for</code>-to-<code>while</code> conversion regarding the loop variable's scope?</p></front>
    <back><p>In the <code>for</code> loop, the variable is scoped to the loop. In the <code>while</code> version, the variable is declared before the loop and remains in scope after it ends.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does an enhanced <code>for</code> loop provide?</p></front>
    <back><p>A concise way to traverse an array or an <code>ArrayList</code> when you only need each element's value and don't care about the index.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop most useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>When you need to process one element at a time and don't need the index of the element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use an enhanced <code>for</code> loop when you need to know the index of each element?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The enhanced <code>for</code> loop does not provide access to the index. Use a standard <code>for</code> loop instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What types can an enhanced <code>for</code> loop iterate over?</p></front>
    <back><p>Arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s (and more generally, any <code>Iterable</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare the enhanced <code>for</code> loop with the standard <code>for</code> loop for array traversal.</p></front>
    <back><p>The enhanced <code>for</code> loop is more concise and avoids index management, but does not provide access to the index. The standard <code>for</code> loop gives full control over indexing.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the header of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop consist of?</p></front>
    <back><p>A variable declaration, a colon, and an expression that evaluates to an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the general syntax of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (Type variable : arrayOrList) { body }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What separates the variable declaration from the collection in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop header?</p></front>
    <back><p>A colon (<code>:</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (String s : names)</code>, what must <code>names</code> be?</p></front>
    <back><p>An array of <code>String</code> or an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> (or any <code>Iterable&lt;String&gt;</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the enhanced <code>for</code> loop header use semicolons like a standard <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It uses a colon to separate the variable declaration from the collection expression, not semicolons.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many times does the body of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop execute?</p></front>
    <back><p>Once for each element of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (int x : arr)</code>, what value does <code>x</code> hold during each iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>The value of each element of <code>arr</code> in turn, starting from the first element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In an enhanced <code>for</code> loop, what order are the elements visited?</p></front>
    <back><p>In order, from the first element to the last.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the loop variable in <code>for (int x : arr)</code> between iterations?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is assigned the value of the next element of <code>arr</code> for each successive iteration.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>arr</code> has 5 elements, how many times does the body of <code>for (int x : arr) { ... }</code> run?</p></front>
    <back><p>Exactly 5 times, once for each element.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In an enhanced <code>for</code> loop, does assigning a new value to the loop variable change the array?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The loop variable is just a regular variable. Assigning a new value to it has no effect on the array itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't you use an enhanced <code>for</code> loop to modify the elements of an array of primitives?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the loop variable is a copy of the array element. Assigning to it changes only the local variable, not the array.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you write <code>for (int x : arr) { x = 0; }</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Nothing changes in <code>arr</code>. The assignment <code>x = 0</code> only changes the local loop variable, not the corresponding array element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the loop variable in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop a reference to the array element or a copy?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a regular variable that receives a copy of each element's value. It is not a direct reference to the array slot.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an enhanced <code>for</code> loop iterates over an <code>ArrayList&lt;StringBuilder&gt;</code>, can you modify the objects through the loop variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The loop variable holds a reference to the object, so calling methods on it (like <code>append</code>) modifies the actual object. But reassigning the variable itself does not change the list.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can the body of a loop contain another loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The body of a loop can contain any statements, including other loops.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a nested loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A loop that appears in the body of another loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you nest a <code>for</code> loop inside a <code>while</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Any type of loop can be nested inside any other type of loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is there a limit to how many levels of loop nesting are allowed?</p></front>
    <back><p>There is no language-imposed limit, though deep nesting reduces readability.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Besides other loops, what else can the body of a loop contain?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any statements: variable declarations, assignments, method calls, conditional statements, and more.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When a loop is nested inside another loop, what must happen before the outer loop can continue to its next iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>The inner loop must complete all of its iterations.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an outer loop runs <code>n</code> times and an inner loop runs <code>m</code> times, how many total iterations does the inner loop execute?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>n * m</code> total iterations, because the inner loop completes fully for each iteration of the outer loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the outer loop proceed to its next iteration while the inner loop is still running?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The inner loop must complete before the outer loop continues.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In nested loops, does the inner loop restart from the beginning on each iteration of the outer loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Each time the outer loop enters the body, the inner loop starts fresh from its initialization.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the total number of times the inner body runs in: <code>for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) { for (int j = 0; j < 4; j++) { ... } }</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>12 times (3 outer iterations times 4 inner iterations).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How can a <code>return</code> statement be used with a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>return</code> statement immediately returns from the current method, which effectively breaks out of any loop the <code>return</code> is inside.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to a loop when a <code>return</code> statement inside it is executed?</p></front>
    <back><p>The loop stops immediately because <code>return</code> exits the entire method, not just the loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does a <code>return</code> statement only exit the innermost loop in a nested loop structure?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>return</code> exits the entire method, which means all enclosing loops are terminated.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give a scenario where you might use <code>return</code> to exit a loop early.</p></front>
    <back><p>Searching an array for a value: once the value is found, <code>return</code> it immediately rather than continuing to iterate through the remaining elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between a <code>return</code> statement and a <code>break</code> statement in a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>return</code> exits the entire method. <code>break</code> exits only the innermost loop and continues with the statement after the loop.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an "off by one" error in the context of loops?</p></front>
    <back><p>An error where the loop iterates one time too many or one time too few, usually due to an incorrect boundary condition.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt;= s.length(); i++)</code> iterating over a string's characters, what is the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is an off-by-one error. Using <code>&lt;=</code> instead of <code>&lt;</code> causes one extra iteration, accessing an index that is out of bounds.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the correct condition for iterating over all characters of a string <code>s</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>i &lt; s.length()</code>, not <code>i &lt;= s.length()</code>, since valid indices go from 0 to <code>s.length() - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why are off-by-one errors common in loops?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the boundary between <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code> (or starting at 0 vs. 1) is easy to get wrong, especially when indices are zero-based.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you check for an off-by-one error in a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Test the boundary cases: verify the first and last iterations use valid values, and count the total number of iterations to confirm it matches expectations.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What causes an unintended infinite loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>The condition never becomes <code>false</code>, often due to a bug in the update code that fails to move the loop toward termination.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a bug that could cause an unintended infinite loop.</p></front>
    <back><p>Incrementing instead of decrementing (or vice versa), or forgetting the update statement entirely, so the loop variable never reaches the terminating value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do unintended infinite loops typically differ from intentional infinite loops?</p></front>
    <back><p>Unintended infinite loops are bugs caused by incorrect update code. Intentional infinite loops (e.g. event loops) are designed to run until explicitly broken out of.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should you check if you suspect a loop is running infinitely?</p></front>
    <back><p>Verify that the update code correctly modifies the variables the condition depends on, so the condition will eventually become <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>for (int i = 10; i > 0; i++)</code>, why is this an infinite loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>i</code> starts at 10 and is incremented, so <code>i > 0</code> is always <code>true</code>. The update should be <code>i--</code> to count down toward 0.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Arrays are a reference type that collects multiple values of a given type into a single value. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Are arrays in Java a primitive type or a reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p>Arrays are a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the purpose of an array in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>An array collects multiple values of a given type into a single value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can a single array hold values of different types, such as both <code>int</code> and <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. An array collects multiple values of a <em>given</em> type; all elements must be the same type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Since arrays are a reference type, what value does an array variable hold?</p></front>
    <back><p>It holds a reference (pointer) to the array object in memory, not the array data itself.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you assign one array variable to another, e.g. <code>int[] b = a;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because arrays are reference types, both variables refer to the same underlying array object. Changes through one variable are visible through the other.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The values in an array are called the elements of the array or sometimes the components. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the standard term for the individual values stored in an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are called the <em>elements</em> of the array (sometimes called <em>components</em>).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is another, less common, name for the elements of an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are sometimes called <em>components</em>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If an array holds the values 3, 7, and 11, how many elements does it have?</p></front>
    <back><p>It has 3 elements.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: "element" and "component" are interchangeable terms when talking about values in an array.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. Both terms refer to the individual values stored in an array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In the declaration <code>int[] nums = {5, 10, 15};</code>, what are 5, 10, and 15 called?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are the elements (or components) of the array <code>nums</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Array elements can be either primitive or reference values. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Can an array in Java hold primitive values like <code>int</code> or <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Array elements can be primitive values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can an array in Java hold reference values like <code>String</code> objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Array elements can be reference values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of an array whose elements are primitive values and one whose elements are reference values.</p></front>
    <back><p>Primitive: <code>int[] nums = {1, 2, 3};</code>. Reference: <code>String[] words = {"hi", "bye"};</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What two broad categories of values can array elements be?</p></front>
    <back><p>Primitive values or reference values.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>String[]</code> a valid array type even though <code>String</code> is a reference type?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Array elements can be reference values, so <code>String[]</code> is perfectly valid.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The size of an array is established at the time of its creation and cannot be changed. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you change the size of a Java array after it has been created?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The size of an array is established at creation time and cannot be changed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When is the size of a Java array determined?</p></front>
    <back><p>At the time of its creation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If you need a collection that can grow and shrink, why can't you use a plain array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because an array's size is fixed at creation and cannot be changed. You would need a resizable collection such as <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you create <code>int[] a = new int[5];</code> and later need to store 10 values?</p></front>
    <back><p>You must create a new, larger array and copy the old elements over, because the original array's size cannot be changed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Compare arrays and <code>ArrayList</code> in terms of resizability.</p></front>
    <back><p>Arrays have a fixed size set at creation. An <code>ArrayList</code> can grow and shrink dynamically.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: When an array is created using new and a size, all elements are initialized with the standard zero value. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What value do elements of <code>new int[10]</code> initially contain?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code>, the default zero value for <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default initial value for elements of a <code>new boolean[5]</code> array?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default initial value for elements of a <code>new double[3]</code> array?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0.0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default initial value for elements of <code>new String[4]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>null</code>, because <code>String</code> is a reference type and all reference types default to <code>null</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are the four standard zero values used to initialize array elements for <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>, and reference types?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code> for <code>int</code>, <code>0.0</code> for <code>double</code>, <code>false</code> for <code>boolean</code>, and <code>null</code> for all reference types.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Initializer lists can be used to create arrays containing specific values. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you create an array containing the specific values 42, 52, and 103?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use an initializer list: <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What determines the length of an array created with an initializer list?</p></front>
    <back><p>The length is set to the number of elements provided in the initializer list.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the length of the array created by <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>3, because three elements are provided.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Compare creating an array with <code>new int[3]</code> versus <code>new int[] { 1, 2, 3 }</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>new int[3]</code> creates an array of length 3 with all elements set to 0. <code>new int[] { 1, 2, 3 }</code> creates an array of length 3 with elements 1, 2, and 3.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the term for the <code>{ 42, 52, 103 }</code> syntax used when creating an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is called an initializer list.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Arrays have a read-only instance variable length which gives the number of elements. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you find out how many elements are in an array <code>xs</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>xs.length</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>length</code> a method or an instance variable on arrays?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a read-only instance variable, not a method. You write <code>arr.length</code>, not <code>arr.length()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you assign a new value to <code>arr.length</code> to resize an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>length</code> is read-only and cannot be assigned to.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>arr.length</code> and <code>str.length()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>arr.length</code> is a read-only instance variable on arrays (no parentheses). <code>str.length()</code> is a method call on <code>String</code> (with parentheses).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>int[] a = {10, 20, 30, 40};</code>, what does <code>a.length</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>4.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Elements are accessed using square brackets and an index. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What syntax is used to access the 0th element of an array <code>xs</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>xs[0]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What characters surround the index when accessing an array element?</p></front>
    <back><p>Square brackets: <code>[]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>String[] names = {"Alice", "Bob", "Carol"};</code>, what does <code>names[1]</code> evaluate to?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"Bob"</code>, because array indexes start at 0.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the index of the first element in any Java array?</p></front>
    <back><p>0. Java arrays are zero-indexed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Given <code>double[] d = new double[5];</code>, write the expression that accesses the last element.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>d[4]</code>, or more generally <code>d[d.length - 1]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The valid indexes for an array are 0 through length - 1, inclusive. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>For an array of length 7, what is the range of valid indexes?</p></front>
    <back><p>0 through 6, inclusive.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the last valid index of an array with <code>length</code> elements?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>length - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is the last valid index <code>length - 1</code> rather than <code>length</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because arrays are zero-indexed, so the first index is 0 and the last is <code>length - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is index <code>-1</code> valid for a Java array?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Valid indexes start at 0.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>int[] a = new int[3];</code>, is <code>a[3]</code> a valid access?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Valid indexes are 0, 1, and 2. Index 3 is out of bounds.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Using an invalid index will cause an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What exception is thrown when you access an array with an index less than 0 or greater than <code>length - 1</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens at runtime if you execute <code>int[] a = new int[3]; int x = a[5];</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because 5 is not a valid index.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> a compile-time error or a runtime error?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a runtime error (exception). The compiler does not check index bounds.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What two conditions on an index value will cause an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>If the index is less than 0, or if the index is greater than <code>length - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Given <code>int[] a = new int[4];</code>, which of these throw an exception: <code>a[-1]</code>, <code>a[0]</code>, <code>a[3]</code>, <code>a[4]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>a[-1]</code> and <code>a[4]</code> throw <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>. <code>a[0]</code> and <code>a[3]</code> are valid.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: An array access expression can be used to obtain a value or as a place that can be assigned. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Can an array access expression like <code>xs[2]</code> appear on the left side of an assignment?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. An array access expression can be used as a place to assign a value, e.g. <code>xs[2] = 10;</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the expression <code>xs[0] += 5;</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It adds 5 to the current value of <code>xs[0]</code> and stores the result back in <code>xs[0]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use the <code>++</code> operator on an array element like <code>nums[3]++</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, if the array holds numbers. The array access expression acts like a variable and supports compound assignment operators.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In what two ways can an array access expression be used?</p></front>
    <back><p>To obtain (read) a value, or as a target (lvalue) that can be assigned a value.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How is an array access expression similar to a variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Like a variable, it can be used to read a value or as a place to store a value via <code>=</code> or compound assignment operators like <code>+=</code> and <code>++</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Looping over the individual elements of an array is also called traversing the array. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the term for looping over every element of an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traversing the array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to "traverse" an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>It means to loop over (visit) the individual elements of the array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is "traversing an array" different from "iterating over an array"?</p></front>
    <back><p>No, they mean the same thing: looping over the individual elements of the array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If you write a <code>for</code> loop that prints every element of an array, what are you doing to the array?</p></front>
    <back><p>You are traversing the array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What types of loops can be used to traverse an array?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for</code> loops, <code>while</code> loops, and enhanced <code>for</code> (for-each) loops.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Traversing with a standard for or while loop requires using an index. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>When traversing an array with a standard <code>for</code> loop, what must you use to access each element?</p></front>
    <back><p>An index variable to access each element via <code>arr[i]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Write a standard <code>for</code> loop header that traverses an array <code>arr</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; arr.length; i++)</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does a <code>while</code> loop traversal of an array require an index?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>while</code> loops do not have a built-in loop variable; you must manually maintain an index to access each element by position.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Compare traversing an array with a standard <code>for</code> loop versus an enhanced <code>for</code> loop in terms of index access.</p></front>
    <back><p>A standard <code>for</code> loop requires an explicit index variable. An enhanced <code>for</code> loop gives you each element directly without an index.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When would you prefer a standard <code>for</code> loop over an enhanced <code>for</code> loop for array traversal?</p></front>
    <back><p>When you need the index of each element, for example to modify elements in place or to compare adjacent elements.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- 2D ARRAYS -->

  <!-- Item: 2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How are 2D arrays stored internally in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>As arrays of arrays. A 2D array is a 1D array whose elements are themselves 1D arrays.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is creating and indexing a 2D array similar to working with a 1D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because 2D arrays are stored as arrays of arrays, so the same creation and indexing rules apply at each level.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the type of <code>arr[0]</code> if <code>arr</code> is declared as <code>int[][] arr</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int[]</code> &mdash; a 1D array of <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a 2D array is really an array of arrays, is it possible for different rows to have different lengths?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Since each row is an independent 1D array, rows can have different lengths (called a "ragged" or "jagged" array).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>new int[3][4]</code> relate to the concept of "arrays of arrays"?</p></front>
    <back><p>It creates a 1D array of length 3, where each element is a 1D <code>int</code> array of length 4.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: It is equally correct to think of a 2d array as a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an alternative way to think about a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>As a 1D array whose elements happen to be arrays.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: A 2D array in Java is a fundamentally different data structure from a 1D array.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. A 2D array is simply a 1D array whose elements are 1D arrays.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If you have <code>int[][] grid</code>, what does <code>grid.length</code> give you?</p></front>
    <back><p>The number of rows (the length of the outer 1D array).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If you have <code>int[][] grid</code>, what does <code>grid[0].length</code> give you?</p></front>
    <back><p>The number of columns in the first row (the length of the inner 1D array at index 0).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How does viewing a 2D array as "a 1D array of arrays" help you understand <code>grid[r]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>grid[r]</code> retrieves one element of the outer 1D array, which is itself an entire 1D array representing row <code>r</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The square brackets [row][col] are used to access and modify an element in a 2d array. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you access the element at row 2, column 3 of a 2D array <code>grid</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>grid[2][3]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the expression <code>arr[1][4] = 99;</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It modifies the element at row 1, column 4 of the 2D array <code>arr</code>, setting it to 99.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many sets of square brackets are needed to access a single element of a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two: one for the row index and one for the column index.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>arr[row][col]</code>, what does the first index select and what does the second index select?</p></front>
    <back><p>The first index selects the row (the inner array), and the second index selects the column (the element within that inner array).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you both read and write a 2D array element using the <code>[row][col]</code> syntax?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The bracket syntax is used to both access (read) and modify (write) elements.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: 2d arrays can be initialized with specific values by writing a nested initialization expression. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you create a 2D array with specific initial values?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use a nested initializer list, e.g. <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>int[][] m = { { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } };</code> create?</p></front>
    <back><p>A 2D array with 2 rows and 3 columns, containing 1, 2, 3 in the first row and 4, 5, 6 in the second.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In a nested initializer, what does each inner set of braces represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>One row of the 2D array (one inner 1D array).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is <code>m[1][0]</code> if <code>int[][] m = { { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } };</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>4</code>, the first element of the second row.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use a nested initializer list to create a 2D array where the rows have different lengths?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. For example: <code>int[][] a = { { 1, 2 }, { 3, 4, 5 } };</code> creates rows of length 2 and 3.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: 2d arrays are typically traversed using nested loops. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of loop structure is typically used to traverse a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Nested loops (a loop inside a loop).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why do you need nested loops rather than a single loop to traverse a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because a 2D array has two dimensions (rows and columns), so one loop iterates over rows and another iterates over columns within each row.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many total iterations occur when traversing a 3-by-4 2D array with nested loops?</p></front>
    <back><p>12 iterations (3 rows &times; 4 columns).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In nested <code>for</code> loops traversing a 2D array, which loop typically handles rows and which handles columns?</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer loop handles rows and the inner loop handles columns.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Write nested <code>for</code> loop headers to traverse <code>int[][] grid</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (int r = 0; r &lt; grid.length; r++)</code> and <code>for (int c = 0; c &lt; grid[r].length; c++)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: The outer loop iterates over the arrays and the inner loop iterates over elements of those arrays. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>In nested loops for a 2D array, what does the outer loop iterate over?</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer array, whose elements are 1D arrays (the rows).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In nested loops for a 2D array, what does the inner loop iterate over?</p></front>
    <back><p>The elements of each 1D array (the individual values within a row).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the inner loop's bound use <code>grid[r].length</code> rather than <code>grid.length</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>grid.length</code> is the number of rows, while <code>grid[r].length</code> is the number of columns in row <code>r</code>, which is what the inner loop needs.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>grid</code> is a 2D array, what type is the variable in the outer enhanced <code>for</code> loop: <code>for (??? row : grid)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It must be a 1D array type (e.g. <code>int[]</code>), since each element of the outer array is a 1D array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Explain the relationship between the outer and inner loops when traversing a 2D array stored as arrays of arrays.</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer loop selects each inner array (row). The inner loop then visits each element within that selected row.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: In enhanced for loops for 2D arrays, the outer loop variable is a 1D array type and inner is the element type. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>In an enhanced <code>for</code> loop traversing <code>int[][] grid</code>, what should the outer loop variable type be?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int[]</code>, because each row is a 1D array of <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In an enhanced <code>for</code> loop traversing <code>int[][] grid</code>, what should the inner loop variable type be?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>, the actual element type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Write nested enhanced <code>for</code> loops to traverse <code>int[][] grid</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (int[] row : grid)</code> for the outer loop, and <code>for (int val : row)</code> for the inner loop.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What error would occur if you wrote <code>for (int row : grid)</code> instead of <code>for (int[] row : grid)</code> when traversing a 2D <code>int</code> array?</p></front>
    <back><p>A compile-time error, because each element of the outer array is an <code>int[]</code>, not an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is the outer loop variable type different from the inner loop variable type when using enhanced <code>for</code> loops on a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer loop iterates over rows (each is a 1D array), so its variable type is a 1D array. The inner loop iterates over individual elements, so its variable type is the element type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: On the AP exam, 2D arrays use row-major order: arr[r][c]. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is "row-major order" for a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer array holds 1D arrays representing rows, so elements are accessed as <code>arr[r][c]</code> where <code>r</code> is the row and <code>c</code> is the column.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>On the AP exam, how are 2D arrays always arranged?</p></front>
    <back><p>In row-major order: the outer array holds rows, and you access elements with <code>arr[r][c]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In row-major order, what does the first index in <code>arr[r][c]</code> represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>The row.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In row-major order, what does the second index in <code>arr[r][c]</code> represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>The column.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If a 2D array represents a grid with 5 rows and 3 columns in row-major order, what is <code>arr.length</code> and what is <code>arr[0].length</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>arr.length</code> is 5 (number of rows) and <code>arr[0].length</code> is 3 (number of columns).</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: Column-major order uses arr[c][r]. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>What is "column-major order" for a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>The outer array holds 1D arrays representing columns, so the element at row <code>r</code> and column <code>c</code> is accessed as <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How does column-major order differ from row-major order in the indexing expression?</p></front>
    <back><p>In row-major order you write <code>arr[r][c]</code>; in column-major order you write <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is column-major order used on the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The AP exam always uses row-major order.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In column-major order, what does the outer array represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>An array of columns, where each element is a 1D array representing one column.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it important to know whether a 2D array uses row-major or column-major order?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the meaning of the first and second index is swapped, so using the wrong order would access the wrong element.</p></back>
  </card>

  <!-- Item: All algorithms that work with 1d arrays will work with 2d arrays, as long as they apply to arrays whose elements are arrays. -->

  <card>
    <front><p>Can algorithms designed for 1D arrays be applied to 2D arrays?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, as long as those algorithms apply to arrays whose elements are themselves arrays.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why do 1D array algorithms transfer to 2D arrays?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because a 2D array is stored as a 1D array of arrays, so any algorithm that works on 1D arrays can operate on the outer array or on each inner array.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>If you have a method that finds the maximum value in a 1D <code>int</code> array, how could you use it with a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Call it on each row (inner 1D array) of the 2D array, then take the maximum of the per-row results.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a 1D array algorithm that naturally extends to 2D arrays.</p></front>
    <back><p>Searching: you can search each row for a value, or search the outer array for a row matching certain criteria.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What must be true about a 1D array algorithm for it to work correctly on a 2D array?</p></front>
    <back><p>It must be applicable to arrays whose elements are arrays (i.e., it must handle the element type being an array).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What three kinds of members make up the structure of a Java class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Variables, constructors, and methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does a class define for many objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>A common structure made up of variables, constructors, and methods (collectively called the "members" of the class).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the collective term for the variables, constructors, and methods inside a class?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are called the "members" of the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: A class only defines methods, not variables or constructors.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. A class defines variables, constructors, and methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you write <code>class Dog { ... }</code>, what have you defined beyond just the code inside?</p></front>
    <back><p>You have defined a common structure (variables, constructors, and methods) that many <code>Dog</code> objects can share.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>In what three places can a class name be used as a type?</p></front>
    <back><p>In variable declarations, as the return type of a method, and as the type of element in an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you define a new class in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>You also define a new type that can be used anywhere a type is needed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a class name be used as the element type of an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Defining a class creates a new type usable in variable declarations, method return types, and as the element type of arrays or <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you define a class called <code>Widget</code>, which of these is valid: <code>Widget w;</code>, <code>ArrayList&lt;Widget&gt; list;</code>, or both?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both are valid. Defining a class creates a type usable in variable declarations and as an <code>ArrayList</code> element type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: You can use a class name as the return type of a method.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. Defining a class defines a new type that can be used as a method's return type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an object in relation to a class?</p></front>
    <back><p>An object is a single instance of a class whose data lives somewhere in memory distinct from all other objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do two objects of the same class share the same memory for their data?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Each object's data lives in its own distinct location in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What distinguishes one object from another object of the same class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each object is a separate instance with its own data stored in a distinct location in memory.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you create two <code>Point</code> objects, do they occupy the same memory?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Each object is a single instance whose data lives in memory distinct from all other objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What term describes a single concrete realization of a class that exists in memory?</p></front>
    <back><p>An object (also called an "instance" of the class).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What keyword marks a variable or method as belonging to the class rather than to instances?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>static</code> keyword.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are non-static variables and methods also known as?</p></front>
    <back><p>"Instance variables" and "instance methods."</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you distinguish a static member from a non-static member in Java source code?</p></front>
    <back><p>A static member is marked with the <code>static</code> keyword; a non-static member lacks it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: A method without the <code>static</code> keyword is called a static method.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. A method without <code>static</code> is a non-static (instance) method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two categories can class members fall into based on the <code>static</code> keyword?</p></front>
    <back><p>Static members (marked with <code>static</code>) and non-static members (instance variables and instance methods).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the <code>static</code> keyword appear relative to the access modifier and type in a declaration?</p></front>
    <back><p>After the access modifier (<code>public</code> or <code>private</code>) and before the type, e.g. <code>public static int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can static variables and methods be marked <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Static members can be marked either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the correct order of keywords for a public static integer variable?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public static int</code> — access modifier, then <code>static</code>, then the type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>static public int count;</code> valid, and what is the conventional order?</p></front>
    <back><p>It compiles, but the conventional order is access modifier first: <code>public static int count;</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the declaration for a private static double variable named <code>rate</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>private static double rate;</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How many copies of a static variable exist, regardless of how many objects are created?</p></front>
    <back><p>Exactly one. A static variable represents a single value stored in the class itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where is a static variable stored?</p></front>
    <back><p>In the class itself, not in any individual object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If 100 objects of a class exist, how many copies of a static variable does that class have?</p></front>
    <back><p>Still just one. The static variable is shared by all instances.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to a static variable's value when one instance modifies it?</p></front>
    <back><p>All instances see the change because the static variable is a single value shared by the whole class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare where an instance variable's value lives versus where a static variable's value lives.</p></front>
    <back><p>An instance variable's value lives in each individual object; a static variable's single value lives in the class itself and is shared by all instances.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What restriction applies to what static methods can access?</p></front>
    <back><p>Static methods can only access static variables and call other static methods (unless they have a reference to an instance).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a static method directly access an instance variable without any object reference?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Static methods can only directly access static variables and other static methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't a static method directly use <code>this</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because static methods belong to the class, not to any instance, so there is no <code>this</code> reference. They can only access static members directly.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to reference an instance variable inside a static method without an object reference?</p></front>
    <back><p>You get a compile-time error. Static methods can only access static variables directly.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a static method call an instance method if it has been passed an object as a parameter?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A static method can access instance members through a reference to an object, such as one passed as an argument.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How are static members typically accessed?</p></front>
    <back><p>Using the class name and the dot operator, e.g. <code>Math.PI</code> and <code>Math.abs()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What syntax do you use to call the static method <code>abs</code> in the <code>Math</code> class?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.abs()</code> — the class name, a dot, and the method name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> an example of accessing a static variable or an instance variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>A static variable. Static members are accessed using the class name and the dot operator.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you access a static member through an object reference instead of the class name?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, but it is not typical. The conventional approach is to use the class name and the dot operator.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What operator connects a class name to a static member when accessing it?</p></front>
    <back><p>The dot operator, e.g. <code>Math.PI</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where is an object's state stored?</p></front>
    <back><p>In its instance variables. Each object has its own values for its instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do two objects of the same class share instance variable values?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Each object has its own separate values for its instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What term describes the data that an individual object holds?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object's state, which is stored in its instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you create two <code>Circle</code> objects with different radii, where is each radius stored?</p></front>
    <back><p>In each object's own instance variable. Each object maintains its own values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What changes when you modify an instance variable of one object — does it affect other objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Each object has its own instance variable values, so changing one does not affect others.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of relationship do instance variables create between an object and the values stored in them?</p></front>
    <back><p>A "has-a" relationship, as in a <code>Point</code> has an x and y value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a "has-a" relationship differ from an "is-a" relationship in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>"Has-a" comes from instance variables (e.g. a <code>Point</code> has an x). "Is-a" comes from one class extending another (inheritance).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>Car</code> class has an instance variable of type <code>Engine</code>, what relationship does that represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>A "has-a" relationship: a <code>Car</code> has an <code>Engine</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What Java keyword creates an "is-a" relationship, as opposed to the "has-a" relationship from instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>extends</code> keyword (inheritance).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a "has-a" relationship using the <code>Point</code> class.</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>Point</code> has an x value and a y value, stored in its instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What access modifier are instance variables typically given?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the access modifier appear in an instance variable declaration?</p></front>
    <back><p>Before the variable type, e.g. <code>private int n</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can instance variables be marked <code>public</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, they can be marked <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>, but they are typically made <code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why are instance variables typically made <code>private</code> rather than <code>public</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>To control access to the object's state and support encapsulation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a typical instance variable declaration for a <code>String</code> called <code>name</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>private String name;</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are constructors used for in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Constructors are invoked to create objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does a constructor's signature consist of?</p></front>
    <back><p>The constructor name (which always matches the class name) and a parameter list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Must a constructor's name match the class name?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A constructor's name always matches the class name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does a constructor have a return type?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Unlike methods, constructors do not have a return type — their signature is just the name and parameter list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when a constructor is invoked?</p></front>
    <back><p>A new object is created and its state is initialized according to the constructor's code.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What keyword is used to call a constructor and create a new object?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>new</code> keyword, followed by the class name and an argument list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the syntax for creating a new <code>Dog</code> object using a constructor that takes a <code>String</code> name.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>new Dog("Rex")</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What must the argument list in a constructor call correspond to?</p></front>
    <back><p>One of the class's constructors — the arguments must match a constructor's parameter list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which class in Java can have objects created without using the <code>new</code> keyword?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>. String objects can be created using literal strings (e.g. <code>"hello"</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Besides <code>String</code> literals, what other mechanism can create objects without an explicit <code>new</code> call?</p></front>
    <back><p>Autoboxing of primitive types can create new instances of wrapper types (e.g. <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>) without explicitly calling a constructor.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the primary job of a constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>To initialize the state of an object and leave it in a usable state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What do constructors often do with the values passed as arguments?</p></front>
    <back><p>Assign them to the object's instance variables to set up its initial state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean for a constructor to leave an object in a "usable state"?</p></front>
    <back><p>After the constructor finishes, the object's instance variables should be properly initialized so the object can function correctly.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>Rectangle</code> constructor takes <code>width</code> and <code>height</code>, what does it typically do with them?</p></front>
    <back><p>It assigns them to instance variables, e.g. <code>this.width = width; this.height = height;</code>, initializing the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if a constructor fails to initialize all instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object may not be in a usable state. The job of a constructor is to fully initialize the object.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do constructor parameter lists work compared to method parameter lists?</p></front>
    <back><p>They work just like method parameter lists — they define local variables initialized with the values of the arguments passed to the constructor call.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should constructor arguments provide?</p></front>
    <back><p>The data needed to initialize the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are constructor parameters local variables or instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Local variables. They are defined by the parameter list and initialized with the argument values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the scope of a constructor's parameters?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are local to the constructor, just like method parameters are local to a method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a constructor parameter has the same name as an instance variable, how do you refer to the instance variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>this.variableName</code> to refer to the instance variable, since the parameter name shadows it.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when no constructor is written in a Java class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Java provides a no-argument constructor and all instance variables are set to default values for their type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the default values for <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>, and reference types when using the default constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code> for <code>int</code>, <code>0.0</code> for <code>double</code>, <code>false</code> for <code>boolean</code>, and <code>null</code> for all reference types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default value of a <code>boolean</code> instance variable when no constructor initializes it?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a class has no constructor, what type of constructor does Java automatically provide?</p></front>
    <back><p>A no-argument (default) constructor.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the default value of a <code>String</code> instance variable when no constructor is written?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>null</code>, since <code>String</code> is a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What risk arises when a mutable object is passed to a constructor and stored in an instance variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any mutations made to that object by the class will change the state for all code that holds a reference to it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you avoid unintended side effects when a mutable object is passed to a constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>Store a copy of the argument instead of the original reference.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an <code>ArrayList</code> is passed to a constructor and stored directly, what happens when the caller modifies the original list?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object's instance variable refers to the same list, so it sees the caller's changes too.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is it acceptable to store a mutable argument directly (without copying) in a constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>When sharing the reference is intentional — when the whole point is for the class to work with the same object the caller has.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What concept is being applied when a constructor copies a mutable argument before storing it?</p></front>
    <back><p>Defensive copying — preventing external code from mutating the object's internal state through a shared reference.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What defines an object's behavior?</p></front>
    <back><p>The methods in its class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is meant by "an object's behavior"?</p></front>
    <back><p>What we can do with the object, as defined by the methods in its class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where do you look to determine what operations you can perform on an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>At the methods defined in the object's class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do methods and instance variables work together in a class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Instance variables store the object's state, while methods define its behavior — what we can do with it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>BankAccount</code> class has methods <code>deposit</code> and <code>withdraw</code>, what do those define?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object's behavior — what we can do with a <code>BankAccount</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between how instance methods and static methods are called?</p></front>
    <back><p>Instance methods are called on objects of the class; <code>static</code> methods are called on the class itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Given <code>String s = "hello";</code>, is <code>s.length()</code> calling an instance method or a static method?</p></front>
    <back><p>An instance method, because it is called on an object (<code>s</code>) rather than on the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Math.max(3, 5)</code> an instance method call or a static method call?</p></front>
    <back><p>A static method call, because it is called on the class <code>Math</code> rather than on an object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>On what do you call an instance method?</p></front>
    <back><p>On an object (instance) of the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>On what do you call a static method?</p></front>
    <back><p>On the class itself, using the class name.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What can instance methods access that static methods cannot (directly)?</p></front>
    <back><p>All of an object's instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can an instance method read and modify the object's instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Instance methods have access to all of the object's instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can instance methods access instance variables while static methods cannot?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because instance methods are called on a specific object, so they have a <code>this</code> reference to that object's instance variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an instance method and a static method both need to use a value, where should that value be stored?</p></front>
    <back><p>In a static variable, since static methods can only access static variables directly.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: An instance method can access both instance variables and static variables.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. Instance methods have access to all instance variables and can also access static members.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a "getter" method?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method that takes no arguments and simply returns the value of an instance variable. Also called an "accessor."</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the more formal name for a getter method?</p></front>
    <back><p>An accessor.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why are getter methods used instead of making instance variables public?</p></front>
    <back><p>They give code outside the class access to the object's state without making instance variables public, supporting encapsulation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the typical signature pattern of a getter for a <code>private int age</code> field?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public int getAge()</code> — no parameters, returns the value of the instance variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many parameters does a getter method take?</p></front>
    <back><p>None. A getter takes no arguments and returns the value of an instance variable.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a "setter" method?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method that returns <code>void</code>, takes a single argument, and assigns it to an instance variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the more general term for methods that change any part of an object's state?</p></front>
    <back><p>Mutators.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a setter differ from a general mutator?</p></front>
    <back><p>A setter specifically assigns a single argument to one instance variable. A mutator is any method that changes any part of the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What return type does a setter method have?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>void</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a typical setter signature for a <code>private String name</code> field.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public void setName(String name)</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do the keywords <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> control in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>What code can access class members.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the general term for <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Access modifiers.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many access modifiers are covered in the AP CSA curriculum?</p></front>
    <back><p>Two: <code>public</code> and <code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do access modifiers apply only to variables, or also to methods and constructors?</p></front>
    <back><p>They apply to all class members: variables, methods, and constructors.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What aspect of a class do access modifiers define?</p></front>
    <back><p>The visibility of class members — which code is allowed to access them.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>private</code> keyword restrict access to?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only code within the declaring class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>public</code> keyword allow?</p></front>
    <back><p>Access from any code, regardless of what class it is in.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a subclass directly access a <code>private</code> member of its superclass?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>private</code> restricts access to only code within the declaring class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare the scope of <code>public</code> vs. <code>private</code> access.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>private</code> limits access to the declaring class only; <code>public</code> allows access from any code anywhere.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method is marked <code>private</code>, can code in a different class call it?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>private</code> members can only be accessed by code within the declaring class.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can a class be marked <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Classes cannot be marked <code>private</code> and are typically marked <code>public</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What access modifier are classes typically given?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many <code>public</code> classes can a single <code>.java</code> file contain?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only one. Additional top-level classes in the file must leave off the <code>public</code> modifier.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to declare a top-level class as <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is not allowed. Top-level classes cannot be <code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a <code>.java</code> file has two top-level classes, what is the access rule?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only one can be <code>public</code>; the other must omit the <code>public</code> modifier.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why should instance variables usually be made <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>To keep access to variables internal to the class, supporting encapsulation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the typical access modifier for instance variables?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What problem arises if instance variables are made <code>public</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any code can directly read and modify the object's state, bypassing any validation or control the class might provide.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: Instance variables should usually be accessible from outside the class.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. Instance variables are usually made <code>private</code> to keep access internal to the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does making instance variables <code>private</code> relate to encapsulation?</p></front>
    <back><p>It hides the implementation details of the class, forcing external code to use methods to interact with the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What access modifier are constructors typically given?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When might a class have a <code>private</code> constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>When the constructor is only used within the class, either from other constructors or from methods that construct new instances.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a constructor be <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Sometimes classes have <code>private</code> constructors that are only used internally.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of why a class might use a <code>private</code> constructor.</p></front>
    <back><p>A factory method in the class might call the <code>private</code> constructor to control how instances are created.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If all constructors of a class are <code>private</code>, can code outside the class create instances with <code>new</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. External code cannot access <code>private</code> constructors, so it cannot directly create instances.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Are methods more commonly <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Methods are equally likely to be <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What do <code>public</code> methods define about a class?</p></front>
    <back><p>They define what we can do with instances of the class — the class's public interface.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why are <code>private</code> methods useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>For breaking up big methods into sub-methods that are only useful within the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a "helper method"?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>private</code> method used to break up larger methods into smaller, more manageable sub-methods within the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can code outside a class call a <code>private</code> method of that class?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>private</code> methods can only be called from within the declaring class.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can code within a class access <code>private</code> members of a different instance of the same class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Code within a class can access the <code>private</code> variables and methods of any instance of that class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an <code>equals</code> method in class <code>Point</code> receives another <code>Point</code> as a parameter, can it access that other object's <code>private</code> fields?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Code within a class can access <code>private</code> members of any instance of the same class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>private</code> mean "only accessible to this object"?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>private</code> means accessible to any code within the declaring class, including code operating on other instances of the same class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it useful that code in a class can access private members of other instances of the same class?</p></front>
    <back><p>It allows methods like <code>equals</code> or <code>compareTo</code> to directly compare the internal state of two objects of the same class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: <code>private</code> access is per-object, not per-class.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. <code>private</code> access is per-class: any code in the class can access <code>private</code> members of any instance of that class.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is encapsulation?</p></front>
    <back><p>A technique in which implementation details of a class are kept hidden from code outside the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does encapsulation hide?</p></front>
    <back><p>The implementation details of a class, keeping them hidden from external code.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is encapsulation beneficial?</p></front>
    <back><p>It allows a class to change its internal implementation without affecting code outside the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is encapsulation about hiding data, hiding implementation, or both?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is about hiding implementation details from code outside the class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does encapsulation relate to the <code>private</code> keyword?</p></front>
    <back><p>Marking members <code>private</code> is the primary mechanism for encapsulation — it hides implementation details from external code.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What four options do programmers have when deciding how to expose a class's state?</p></front>
    <back><p>Data can be accessible, modifiable, both, or neither from external code.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean for data to be "accessible but not modifiable"?</p></front>
    <back><p>External code can read the data (e.g. via a getter) but cannot change it (no setter or mutator is provided).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you make a piece of state both accessible and modifiable from outside the class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Provide both a getter (accessor) and a setter (mutator) for it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you make data in a class neither accessible nor modifiable from outside?</p></front>
    <back><p>Make the instance variable <code>private</code> and provide no getter or setter for it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What design decision does encapsulation require programmers to make about each piece of state?</p></front>
    <back><p>Whether to make it accessible, modifiable, both, or neither from external code.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How is state encapsulated in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>By storing it in <code>private</code> instance variables and controlling access through getter, setter, and other mutator methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What role do getters and setters play in encapsulation?</p></front>
    <back><p>They control how external code can access and modify the <code>private</code> instance variables, providing controlled access to the object's state.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a class has a <code>private</code> instance variable with a getter but no setter, is the state accessible, modifiable, or both?</p></front>
    <back><p>Accessible but not modifiable (read-only from outside the class).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two things are needed to encapsulate a piece of state?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>private</code> instance variable and the appropriate getter, setter, or mutator methods to control access.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can encapsulation be achieved if instance variables are <code>public</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Encapsulation requires <code>private</code> instance variables so access is controlled through methods.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the <code>toString</code> method originate?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is inherited from <code>java.lang.Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>toString</code> frequently overridden?</p></front>
    <back><p>To provide a concise, human-readable representation of an object instead of the default (class name and hash code).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does every Java class have a <code>toString</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Every class inherits <code>toString</code> from <code>java.lang.Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the default <code>toString</code> from <code>Object</code> typically return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The class name followed by <code>@</code> and the object's hash code (not very human-readable).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does "overriding" <code>toString</code> mean?</p></front>
    <back><p>Writing a new version of <code>toString</code> in your class that replaces the one inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you pass an object to <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The object's <code>toString</code> method is called, and the returned <code>String</code> is printed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you write <code>System.out.print(myDog);</code> and <code>Dog</code> overrides <code>toString</code>, what gets printed?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>String</code> returned by <code>myDog.toString()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>System.out.println</code> explicitly call <code>toString</code>, or does it happen automatically?</p></front>
    <back><p>It happens automatically. When an object is passed, its <code>toString</code> method is called and the result is printed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the output of <code>System.out.println(obj)</code> if <code>obj</code>'s class does not override <code>toString</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The default from <code>Object</code>: the class name, <code>@</code>, and the hash code (e.g. <code>MyClass@1a2b3c</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which two <code>System.out</code> methods automatically call <code>toString</code> when passed an object?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When is <code>toString</code> called automatically besides in print statements?</p></front>
    <back><p>When a reference type is included in a <code>String</code> concatenation expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Value: " + obj</code> do if <code>obj</code> is an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>It calls <code>obj.toString()</code> and concatenates the resulting <code>String</code> with <code>"Value: "</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does <code>"Score: " + player</code> produce a readable string if <code>Player</code> overrides <code>toString</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>String</code> concatenation automatically calls <code>toString</code> on reference types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Name two situations where Java automatically calls <code>toString</code> on an object.</p></front>
    <back><p>When the object is passed to <code>System.out.print</code>/<code>println</code>, and when it appears in a <code>String</code> concatenation expression.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What would <code>"Result: " + myObj</code> produce if <code>myObj</code>'s class does not override <code>toString</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Something like <code>"Result: MyClass@1a2b3c"</code> — the default <code>toString</code> from <code>Object</code> is used in the concatenation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Within a non-<code>static</code> method or constructor, what does the keyword <code>this</code> refer to?</p></front>
    <back><p>It refers to the current object -- the object on which the method was called or the object being constructed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can <code>this</code> be used inside a <code>static</code> method? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>this</code> refers to the current object, and <code>static</code> methods are not called on an object, so there is no current object for <code>this</code> to reference.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a constructor for class <code>Foo</code> needs to pass the object it is building to another method, what keyword would it use?</p></front>
    <back><p>It would use <code>this</code>, which refers to the object currently being constructed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a non-<code>static</code> method of class <code>Dog</code>, what is the type of the expression <code>this</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The type of <code>this</code> is <code>Dog</code> -- it always has the type of the class in which it appears.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is one common use of <code>this</code> when a constructor parameter has the same name as an instance variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>You use <code>this.variableName</code> to distinguish the instance variable from the parameter, e.g. <code>this.name = name;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of how <code>this</code> can be used as an argument in a method call.</p></front>
    <back><p>A method can pass the current object to another method, e.g. <code>someList.add(this);</code>, which adds the current object to <code>someList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can <code>this</code> be used on the right-hand side of an assignment statement? If so, give an example.</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. You can assign <code>this</code> anywhere a value of the current class type is needed, e.g. <code>Dog d = this;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When you pass <code>this</code> to a constructor of another class, what are you giving that constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>You are giving it a reference to the current object so the newly constructed object can store or use it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Could you return <code>this</code> from a method? What would the return type need to be?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The return type must be the type of the current class (or a supertype), since <code>this</code> is a reference to the current object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to assign a new value to <code>this</code>, e.g. <code>this = new Dog();</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It will not compile. <code>this</code> is not a variable you can reassign; it is a fixed reference to the current object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are comments executed when a Java program runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Comments are ignored by the compiler and are not executed when the program is run.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to comments during compilation?</p></front>
    <back><p>The compiler ignores them entirely. They have no effect on the compiled bytecode.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you put incorrect Java code inside a <code>/* */</code> comment, will the program still compile?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because comments are completely ignored by the compiler.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do programmers write comments if they have no effect on how the program runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>Comments explain the code to human readers, making it easier to understand, maintain, and debug.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does adding or removing comments change the behavior of a Java program?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Since comments are ignored by the compiler, adding or removing them never changes program behavior.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three types of comments in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>/* */</code> for block comments, <code>//</code> for single-line comments, and <code>/** */</code> for Javadoc comments used to create API documentation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What distinguishes a Javadoc comment (<code>/** */</code>) from a regular block comment (<code>/* */</code>)?</p></front>
    <back><p>Javadoc comments are used to generate API documentation and start with <code>/**</code>, while regular block comments start with <code>/*</code> and are just for human readers.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which comment syntax would you use to write a single-line note about a tricky line of code?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>//</code> -- the single-line comment syntax. Everything after <code>//</code> on that line is a comment.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>You want to temporarily disable a 10-line block of code. Which comment style is most practical?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>/* */</code> block comments, since they can span multiple lines without needing a marker on each line.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What tool processes <code>/** */</code> comments to produce documentation?</p></front>
    <back><p>The Javadoc tool, which extracts <code>/** */</code> comments and generates HTML API documentation from them.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is an invariant in programming?</p></front>
    <back><p>An invariant is something that must be true if the program is working correctly. Invariants help us reason about how different parts of a program work together.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do invariants help programmers?</p></front>
    <back><p>They help us think about how different parts of a program work together by defining conditions that must hold true for correct operation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an invariant is violated during program execution, what does that indicate?</p></front>
    <back><p>It indicates the program is not working correctly -- there is a bug somewhere.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between preconditions, postconditions, and invariants?</p></front>
    <back><p>Preconditions and postconditions are specific kinds of invariants -- a precondition must hold before a method call, and a postcondition must hold after it returns.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of an invariant for a class that stores a person's age.</p></front>
    <back><p>The age field is always non-negative. If the age is ever negative, the program has a bug.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a precondition?</p></front>
    <back><p>A precondition is a kind of invariant that defines a condition that must be true before a method is called.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Who is responsible for ensuring that a method's preconditions are met?</p></front>
    <back><p>The caller of the method. If the preconditions are not met, it is a bug in the calling code, not in the method itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A method requires that its parameter is positive, but the caller passes -1. Where is the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>The bug is in the calling code, because it violated the precondition that the parameter must be positive.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is a method required to check whether its preconditions have been met?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Methods may or may not actually check that their preconditions have been met.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare preconditions and postconditions: when must each be true?</p></front>
    <back><p>A precondition must be true <em>before</em> a method is called. A postcondition must be true <em>after</em> a method returns successfully.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a postcondition?</p></front>
    <back><p>A postcondition is a kind of invariant that defines a condition that must always be true after a method returns successfully.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two aspects can a postcondition describe?</p></front>
    <back><p>The value returned by the method and/or any changes to the state of the world (side effects).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A method's postcondition says it returns a sorted array, but it returns an unsorted one. Assuming preconditions were met, where is the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>The bug is in the method itself, because it failed to satisfy its postcondition even though preconditions were met.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a postcondition involve changes to object state rather than just a return value?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Postconditions describe the outcome in terms of the return value <em>and/or</em> changes to the state of the world.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method has no return value (<code>void</code>), can it still have a postcondition?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The postcondition would describe changes to the state of the world, such as modifications to instance variables or other side effects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the "job" of a method in terms of preconditions and postconditions?</p></front>
    <back><p>The job of a method is to satisfy its postconditions, assuming its preconditions have been met.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method's preconditions were met but its postconditions are not satisfied, where is the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>The bug is in the method itself, since it failed to do its job despite being called correctly.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a method's preconditions were <em>not</em> met and it produces incorrect results, where is the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>The bug is in the code that called the method, because the caller failed to satisfy the preconditions.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are methods required to check their preconditions before executing?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Methods may or may not actually check that their preconditions have been met. It is the caller's responsibility to ensure them.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A method documents that its parameter must be non-null but does not check. A caller passes <code>null</code> and gets a <code>NullPointerException</code>. Who has the bug?</p></front>
    <back><p>The caller has the bug. The precondition requires a non-null argument, and the caller violated it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean for constructors to be overloaded?</p></front>
    <back><p>A class has multiple constructors with different numbers or types of parameters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A class has <code>Foo()</code>, <code>Foo(int x)</code>, and <code>Foo(String s)</code>. Are these constructors overloaded?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. They are in the same class and have different parameter types or counts, so they are overloaded.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can constructors in different classes be considered overloaded with respect to each other?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Overloading applies to multiple constructors in the <em>same</em> class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What determines which overloaded constructor is called when you write <code>new Foo(42)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The compiler matches the argument types in the call to the parameter types of the available constructors and selects the matching one.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does constructor overloading differ from method overloading?</p></front>
    <back><p>Constructor overloading involves multiple constructors in the same class, while method overloading involves multiple methods with the same name in the same class or inheritance hierarchy. Both require different parameter types or counts.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean for methods to be overloaded?</p></front>
    <back><p>There are multiple methods in the same class (or inheritance hierarchy) with the same name but different numbers or types of parameters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can two methods with the same name and same parameter types but different return types be considered overloaded?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Overloading requires different numbers or types of <em>parameters</em>. Different return types alone do not constitute overloading and would cause a compilation error.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can overloaded methods exist across an inheritance hierarchy, or must they be in the same class?</p></front>
    <back><p>They can exist across an inheritance hierarchy. A subclass can have a method with the same name as a superclass method but with different parameters, and that counts as overloading.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A class has <code>print(int x)</code> and <code>print(double x)</code>. If you call <code>print(3.14)</code>, which method runs?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>print(double x)</code> version, because the argument <code>3.14</code> is a <code>double</code>, and the compiler selects the method whose parameter type matches the argument type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Compare overloading and overriding: what is the key difference?</p></front>
    <back><p>Overloading means same name, different parameters (in the same class or hierarchy). Overriding means same name <em>and</em> same parameters in a subclass, replacing the superclass behavior.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When an overloaded method is called, how does Java determine which version to invoke?</p></front>
    <back><p>Java finds the method whose parameter types match the types of the arguments in the call.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you call an overloaded method and no version has parameter types matching your arguments?</p></front>
    <back><p>The code will not compile. The compiler must find a matching (or compatible via widening) overloaded method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is overloading resolved at compile time or at run time?</p></front>
    <back><p>At compile time. The compiler determines which overloaded method to call based on the declared types of the arguments.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>You have <code>add(int, int)</code> and <code>add(double, double)</code>. You call <code>add(1, 2.0)</code>. Which is called?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>add(double, double)</code>, because the <code>int</code> argument <code>1</code> is widened to <code>double</code> to match the <code>(double, double)</code> signature.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the ability to overload methods let you do anything you could not do by giving the methods different names?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Overloading is a convenience; you could achieve the same functionality by simply giving each method a different name.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If overloading adds no new capability, why is it useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>It makes code more readable and convenient by allowing related operations to share a name, so callers don't need to remember multiple distinct method names.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Could you replace all overloaded methods in a class with differently named methods and maintain the same behavior?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Overloading doesn't let you do anything you couldn't do with different names; it's purely a naming convenience.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>A classmate says overloading is essential for polymorphism in Java. Is this correct?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Overloading is a convenience for naming. Polymorphism in Java relies on overriding (same signature in subclasses), not overloading.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the significance of overloading if it adds no unique capability?</p></front>
    <back><p>It improves code clarity and usability by grouping related operations under a single name, but functionally it is equivalent to using distinct names.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What class is the direct or indirect superclass of every other class in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>Object</code> class in the <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you write <code>public class Dog { }</code> without an <code>extends</code> clause, what does <code>Dog</code> extend?</p></front>
    <back><p>It implicitly extends <code>Object</code>, since every class that does not explicitly extend another class directly extends <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>For the AP CSA exam, how much do you need to know about inheritance beyond the <code>Object</code> class?</p></front>
    <back><p>Nothing beyond the fact that <code>Object</code> is the superclass of all classes. The AP exam does not require further knowledge of inheritance.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In which package is the <code>Object</code> class located?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is it possible for a Java class to have no superclass at all?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Every class except <code>Object</code> itself has <code>Object</code> as a direct or indirect superclass.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What two methods do all classes inherit from <code>Object</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> and <code>String toString()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the signature of the <code>equals</code> method inherited from <code>Object</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you never define <code>toString()</code> in your class, can you still call it on an instance?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, because your class inherits <code>toString()</code> from <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where are the <code>equals</code> and <code>toString</code> methods described for the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>In the AP Java Quick Reference.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can you call <code>toString()</code> on any Java object, even one you just created?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because every class inherits <code>toString()</code> from <code>Object</code>, which is the ultimate superclass of all classes.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean when a class overrides the <code>equals</code> or <code>toString</code> methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>The class provides its own class-specific implementation that replaces the default version inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do classes often override <code>toString()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>To provide a meaningful string representation of the object, since the default <code>Object</code> version typically returns something like the class name and hash code.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is correctly implementing an overridden <code>equals</code> method easy or hard?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is surprisingly hard to implement correctly, though the details of how to do so are not part of the AP curriculum.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between overriding <code>equals</code> and overloading it?</p></front>
    <back><p>Overriding means providing a method with the exact same signature (<code>boolean equals(Object other)</code>). Overloading would mean defining <code>equals</code> with different parameter types, which would not replace the inherited version.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you override <code>toString()</code> in your class, can you still access the original <code>Object</code> version?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, by calling <code>super.toString()</code> from within your class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which classes from the <code>java.lang</code> package are commonly used in AP CSA?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, <code>System</code>, <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, <code>Boolean</code>, and <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need an <code>import</code> statement to use <code>String</code> or <code>Math</code> in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. They are in the <code>java.lang</code> package, which is always available in all Java programs without importing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the <code>java.lang</code> package and what makes it special?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is the package containing core classes like <code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, and <code>Object</code>. It is special because it is always automatically available without an <code>import</code> statement.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Name all seven classes from <code>java.lang</code> that you should know for AP CSA.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, <code>System</code>, <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, <code>Boolean</code>, and <code>Object</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why don't you need to write <code>import java.lang.String;</code> at the top of your Java file?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the <code>java.lang</code> package is automatically imported in every Java program.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which commonly used AP CSA class is <em>not</em> in <code>java.lang</code> and must be explicitly imported?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList</code>, which must be imported from <code>java.util</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What import statement do you need to use <code>ArrayList</code> in a Java program?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does <code>ArrayList</code> require an import but <code>String</code> does not?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code> is in <code>java.lang</code>, which is auto-imported. <code>ArrayList</code> is in <code>java.util</code>, which must be explicitly imported.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you forget to import <code>ArrayList</code>, what happens when you try to compile?</p></front>
    <back><p>The compiler will report an error because it cannot find the <code>ArrayList</code> class without the <code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code> statement.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In which package is <code>ArrayList</code> located?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>java.util</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are APIs and libraries in the context of Java programming?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are collections of pre-written classes that provide functionality we can use in our programs without writing the code ourselves.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does API stand for, and what does an API provide to a programmer?</p></front>
    <back><p>Application Programming Interface. It provides a set of classes and methods that programmers can use in their programs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do APIs and libraries relate to the concept of code reuse?</p></front>
    <back><p>They provide pre-built classes so programmers can reuse existing, tested code instead of writing everything from scratch.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a Java library class that you use rather than writing your own implementation.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList</code> from <code>java.util</code> -- it provides a resizable list implementation so you don't have to build one yourself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>java.lang</code> an example of a Java API? Why or why not?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. It is a package of classes (<code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, <code>Object</code>, etc.) that provide functionality programmers can use, which is exactly what an API is.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How are <code>String</code> objects typically created in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are typically created using <code>String</code> literals (e.g., <code>"hello"</code>), though they can also be created using constructors defined in the <code>String</code> class.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between creating a <code>String</code> with a literal versus a constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both produce <code>String</code> objects, but literals are the typical approach. Constructors are available but rarely needed since literals are simpler and more common.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: The only way to create a <code>String</code> object in Java is with a <code>String</code> literal.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. <code>String</code> objects can also be created using constructors defined in the <code>String</code> class, though literals are the typical approach.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a statement that creates a <code>String</code> using a literal and one that uses a constructor.</p></front>
    <back><p>Literal: <code>String s = "hello";</code>. Constructor: <code>String s = new String("hello");</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why might a programmer choose to use a <code>String</code> literal rather than the <code>String</code> constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>Literals are the typical and more concise way to create <code>String</code> objects. Constructors are available but rarely necessary.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that <code>String</code> objects are immutable?</p></front>
    <back><p>Once a <code>String</code> object is created, its content cannot be changed. Methods that appear to modify a <code>String</code> actually produce a new <code>String</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you call <code>toUpperCase()</code> on a <code>String</code>, what happens to the original <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The original <code>String</code> is unchanged. <code>toUpperCase()</code> returns a new <code>String</code> object with all characters converted to upper case.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you try to change a character in an existing <code>String</code> object?</p></front>
    <back><p>You cannot. <code>String</code> objects are immutable, so the original <code>String</code> cannot be modified. You must create a new <code>String</code> instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do many <code>String</code> methods return a new <code>String</code> rather than modifying the existing one?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>String</code> objects are immutable. Since the original cannot be changed, methods must produce and return a new <code>String</code> that reflects the desired modification.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After executing <code>String s = "hello"; s.toUpperCase();</code>, what is the value of <code>s</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>s</code> is still <code>"hello"</code>. The <code>toUpperCase()</code> call returns a new <code>String</code> (<code>"HELLO"</code>), but the result is not assigned back to <code>s</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What operators can be used to concatenate <code>String</code> objects in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>+</code> and <code>+=</code> operators.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>"Hello" + " " + "World"</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A new <code>String</code> object with the value <code>"Hello World"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>String</code> concatenation with <code>+</code> modify either of the original <code>String</code> objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Concatenation produces a new <code>String</code> object. The original <code>String</code> objects remain unchanged because <code>String</code>s are immutable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>+=</code> operator do when used with <code>String</code> objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>It concatenates the right-hand <code>String</code> to the left-hand <code>String</code> and assigns the resulting new <code>String</code> to the left-hand variable.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After <code>String s = "Hi"; s += "!";</code>, what is the value of <code>s</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>s</code> is <code>"Hi!"</code>. The <code>+=</code> operator creates a new <code>String</code> and reassigns <code>s</code> to reference it.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you concatenate a non-<code>String</code> value with a <code>String</code> using <code>+</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The non-<code>String</code> value is implicitly converted to a <code>String</code>. Primitives and <code>null</code> use their standard literal form; reference types use their <code>toString</code> method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>"Value: " + 42</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>String</code> <code>"Value: 42"</code>. The <code>int</code> value <code>42</code> is implicitly converted to the <code>String</code> <code>"42"</code> before concatenation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is a reference type converted to a <code>String</code> during concatenation?</p></front>
    <back><p>By calling its <code>toString</code> method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>"x is " + null</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>String</code> <code>"x is null"</code>. The value <code>null</code> is converted to the <code>String</code> <code>"null"</code> during concatenation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How are primitive values converted when concatenated with a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are converted to their standard literal form. For example, <code>3.14</code> becomes <code>"3.14"</code> and <code>true</code> becomes <code>"true"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is an escape sequence in a Java <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A sequence starting with <code>\</code> that represents a special character. The AP exam uses <code>\"</code> (double quote), <code>\\</code> (backslash), and <code>\n</code> (newline).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What are the three escape sequences used in the AP CS A course?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>\"</code> (double quote character), <code>\\</code> (backslash character), and <code>\n</code> (newline character).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you include a literal double-quote character inside a <code>String</code> literal?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use the escape sequence <code>\"</code>. For example: <code>"She said \"hello\""</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>\n</code> represent in a Java <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A newline character. When printed, it moves the output to the next line.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you include a literal backslash in a Java <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use the escape sequence <code>\\</code>. For example: <code>"C:\\Users\\file"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the range of valid index values for a <code>String</code> of length <code>n</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>n - 1</code> (inclusive).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What exception is thrown when you access an invalid index in a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>For a <code>String</code> of length 5, which index values would cause a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any index less than 0 or greater than or equal to 5 (i.e., 5, 6, 7, ... and -1, -2, ...).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the index equal to the length of a <code>String</code> a valid index?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Valid indices go from 0 to <code>length() - 1</code>. Using an index equal to the length causes a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you call <code>"abc".charAt(-1)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because -1 is outside the valid index range of 0 to 2.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the first character of a <code>String</code> have index 0?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the index represents how many characters are ahead of a given character. The first character has zero characters ahead of it, so its index is 0.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the index of the second character in a <code>String</code>, and why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Index 1, because there is exactly one character ahead of the second character.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is the length of a <code>String</code> not a valid index?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because in an <code>n</code>-character <code>String</code>, no character has <code>n</code> characters in front of it. The last valid index is <code>n - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you think of a <code>String</code> index conceptually?</p></front>
    <back><p>As the number of characters that are in front of (ahead of) a given character in the <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In the <code>String</code> <code>"Java"</code>, what index does <code>'v'</code> have and why?</p></front>
    <back><p>Index 2, because there are two characters (<code>'J'</code> and <code>'a'</code>) ahead of it.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>String(String str)</code> constructor do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It constructs a new <code>String</code> object that represents the same sequence of characters as <code>str</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is there a good reason to use the <code>String(String str)</code> constructor in practice?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. There is almost no reason to ever use this constructor since <code>String</code> literals accomplish the same thing more simply.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the result of <code>new String("hello")</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A new <code>String</code> object containing <code>"hello"</code>, identical in content to the literal <code>"hello"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>new String("hello")</code> considered unnecessary?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because the literal <code>"hello"</code> already creates a <code>String</code> object. Using the constructor creates an extra, redundant object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>The <code>String(String str)</code> constructor is on the AP Java Quick Reference. When should you use it?</p></front>
    <back><p>Almost never. It exists but is rarely needed since <code>String</code> literals are the standard way to create <code>String</code> objects.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>length()</code> method return when called on a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The number of characters in the <code>String</code> object, as an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of the <code>String</code> method <code>length()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Hello".length()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>5</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"".length()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code>, since the empty <code>String</code> contains no characters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>length()</code> related to valid index values of a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Valid indices range from <code>0</code> to <code>length() - 1</code>. The value returned by <code>length()</code> itself is not a valid index.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>substring(int from, int to)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to - 1</code> (i.e., <code>to</code> is exclusive).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Hello".substring(1, 4)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"ell"</code> — characters at indices 1, 2, and 3.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the <code>to</code> parameter in <code>substring(from, to)</code> inclusive or exclusive?</p></front>
    <back><p>Exclusive. The returned substring includes characters from index <code>from</code> up to but not including index <code>to</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the length of the <code>String</code> returned by <code>substring(from, to)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>to - from</code> characters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"abcde".substring(0, 5)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"abcde"</code> — the entire <code>String</code>, since <code>from</code> is 0 and <code>to</code> equals the length.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the one-argument <code>substring(int from)</code> method return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The substring from index <code>from</code> to the end of the <code>String</code>. It is equivalent to <code>substring(from, length())</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Hello".substring(2)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"llo"</code> — all characters from index 2 to the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>substring(from)</code> related to <code>substring(from, to)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>substring(from)</code> is equivalent to <code>substring(from, length())</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Java".substring(0)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"Java"</code> — the entire <code>String</code>, since it starts at index 0 and goes to the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Java".substring(4)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The empty <code>String</code> <code>""</code>, since there are no characters at or after index 4 in a 4-character <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>indexOf(String str)</code> method return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The index of the first occurrence of <code>str</code> in the <code>String</code>, or <code>-1</code> if <code>str</code> is not found.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Hello World".indexOf("World")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>6</code>, because <code>"World"</code> starts at index 6.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>indexOf</code> return if the substring is not found?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>-1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"abcabc".indexOf("bc")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>1</code>, because <code>indexOf</code> returns the index of the first occurrence.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you check whether a <code>String</code> contains a particular substring using <code>indexOf</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Check if <code>indexOf</code> returns a value other than <code>-1</code>. For example: <code>if (s.indexOf("test") != -1)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>equals(Object other)</code> method of <code>String</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>Returns <code>true</code> if <code>other</code> is a <code>String</code> with the same text content; otherwise returns <code>false</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why should you use <code>equals</code> rather than <code>==</code> to compare <code>String</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>==</code> compares references (whether two variables point to the same object), while <code>equals</code> compares the actual text content of the <code>String</code> objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"hello".equals("HELLO")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>false</code>, because <code>equals</code> is case-sensitive.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"abc".equals(42)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>false</code>, because the argument is not a <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the parameter type of the <code>equals</code> method on <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Object</code>. It accepts any object and returns <code>false</code> if the argument is not a <code>String</code> or does not have the same text.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>compareTo(String other)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>A negative value if the <code>String</code> comes alphabetically before <code>other</code>, zero if they are equal, and a positive value if it comes after <code>other</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"apple".compareTo("banana")</code> return: a negative, zero, or positive value?</p></front>
    <back><p>A negative value, because <code>"apple"</code> comes alphabetically before <code>"banana"</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>compareTo</code> return when two <code>String</code>s are equal?</p></front>
    <back><p>Zero.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you determine if one <code>String</code> comes alphabetically after another using <code>compareTo</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>If <code>s1.compareTo(s2)</code> returns a value greater than 0, then <code>s1</code> comes after <code>s2</code> alphabetically.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between <code>compareTo</code> returning 0 and <code>equals</code> returning <code>true</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>If <code>compareTo</code> returns 0, the two <code>String</code>s have identical text, so <code>equals</code> would also return <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>split(String del)</code> method do?</p></front>
    <back><p>Returns a <code>String[]</code> array where each element is a substring of the original <code>String</code>, split around matches of the delimiter <code>del</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"a,b,c".split(",")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>String</code> array <code>{"a", "b", "c"}</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of the <code>split</code> method?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String[]</code> (a <code>String</code> array).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"hello".split("x")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>String</code> array containing one element: <code>{"hello"}</code>, since the delimiter <code>"x"</code> is not found.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"one two three".split(" ")</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>String</code> array <code>{"one", "two", "three"}</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How can you obtain a one-character <code>String</code> at index <code>i</code> in a <code>String</code> <code>s</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>By calling <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>"Hello".substring(0, 1)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>"H"</code> — a one-character <code>String</code> containing the first character.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>substring(i, i + 1)</code> used to get a single character as a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>substring</code> with a range of length 1 (<code>to - from = 1</code>) returns exactly one character as a <code>String</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between getting a character with <code>charAt(i)</code> and <code>substring(i, i + 1)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>charAt(i)</code> returns a <code>char</code> primitive, while <code>substring(i, i + 1)</code> returns a one-character <code>String</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write an expression that gets the last character of <code>String s</code> as a <code>String</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>s.substring(s.length() - 1, s.length())</code>, or equivalently <code>s.substring(s.length() - 1)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What do <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>They display information on the computer monitor (standard output).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the output of <code>System.out.print</code> appear?</p></front>
    <back><p>On the computer monitor (the console or standard output).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What object do <code>print</code> and <code>println</code> belong to in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>System.out</code>, which is the standard output stream.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> both send output to the console.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. Both display information on the computer monitor.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> display different types of data, such as <code>int</code>s and <code>String</code>s?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Both methods can display various types of information on the monitor.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after displaying the output, while <code>print</code> does not.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>System.out.print("A"); System.out.print("B");</code> output?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>AB</code> on the same line, because <code>print</code> does not move the cursor to a new line.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>System.out.println("A"); System.out.println("B");</code> output?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>A</code> on the first line and <code>B</code> on the second line, because <code>println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after each call.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you want to print two values on the same line, should you use <code>print</code> or <code>println</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>print</code>, because it does not move the cursor to a new line after the output.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does calling <code>System.out.println()</code> with no arguments do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It prints nothing but moves the cursor to a new line (outputs a blank line).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is the <code>Math</code> class something you need to import in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The <code>Math</code> class is part of the <code>java.lang</code> package and is available in all Java programs without importing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: You must create a <code>Math</code> object before using its methods.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. The <code>Math</code> class is available in all Java programs and its methods are static, so no object is needed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What makes the <code>Math</code> class universally available in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is part of Java itself and is available in all Java programs without any special setup or import.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need to add any special library to use <code>Math.sqrt</code> in your program?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The <code>Math</code> class is part of Java and available in all programs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In what package is the <code>Math</code> class located?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>java.lang</code>, which is automatically available in all Java programs.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of methods does the <code>Math</code> class contain?</p></front>
    <back><p>Only static methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do you call <code>Math</code> methods using the class name (e.g., <code>Math.abs(x)</code>) rather than on an object?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because all <code>Math</code> methods are static, meaning they belong to the class itself rather than to any instance.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you create an instance of the <code>Math</code> class and call methods on it?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The <code>Math</code> class contains only static methods and is not meant to be instantiated.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: The <code>Math</code> class has both static and non-static methods.</p></front>
    <back><p>False. The <code>Math</code> class contains only static methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that the <code>Math</code> class has only static methods?</p></front>
    <back><p>It means you call all methods on the class itself (e.g., <code>Math.pow(2, 3)</code>) without ever creating a <code>Math</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Which <code>Math</code> methods and constants should you know for the AP CS A exam?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, <code>Math.random</code>, and the constant <code>Math.PI</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> a method or a variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>A variable (not a method). It is a <code>double</code> value that best approximates the mathematical constant pi.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What type is <code>Math.PI</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you compute the area of a circle with radius <code>r</code> using the <code>Math</code> class?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.PI * Math.pow(r, 2)</code> or <code>Math.PI * r * r</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which of the following is NOT a method: <code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.PI</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, <code>Math.random</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.PI</code> is not a method. It is a variable (a <code>double</code> constant).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(int x)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The absolute value of the <code>int</code> parameter <code>x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.abs(int x)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(-7)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>7</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(5)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>5</code>. The absolute value of a positive number is the number itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(0)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(double x)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The absolute value of the <code>double</code> parameter <code>x</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.abs(double x)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.abs(-3.14)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>3.14</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does Java determine whether to call <code>Math.abs(int)</code> or <code>Math.abs(double)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>By the type of the argument. An <code>int</code> argument calls the <code>int</code> version; a <code>double</code> argument calls the <code>double</code> version.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>True or false: <code>Math.abs</code> is overloaded to accept both <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> parameters.</p></front>
    <back><p>True. There are two versions: <code>int abs(int x)</code> and <code>double abs(double x)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.pow(double base, double exponent)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The value of <code>base</code> raised to the power of <code>exponent</code>, as a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.pow(2, 10)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>1024.0</code> (as a <code>double</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.pow(5, 0)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>1.0</code>, because any number raised to the power of 0 is 1.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does <code>Math.pow(3, 2)</code> return <code>9.0</code> instead of <code>9</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>Math.pow</code> always returns a <code>double</code>, even when the mathematical result is a whole number.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(double x)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The positive square root of <code>x</code>, as a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(25)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>5.0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>Math.sqrt</code> return the positive or negative square root?</p></front>
    <back><p>The positive square root.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you compute the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> using <code>Math</code> methods?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.sqrt(Math.pow(a, 2) + Math.pow(b, 2))</code> or <code>Math.sqrt(a * a + b * b)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Math.random()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>A <code>double</code> value greater than or equal to <code>0.0</code> and less than <code>1.0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the value <code>1.0</code> a possible return value of <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>Math.random()</code> returns values from <code>0.0</code> (inclusive) to <code>1.0</code> (exclusive).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the value <code>0.0</code> a possible return value of <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The range is greater than or equal to <code>0.0</code> and less than <code>1.0</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>Math.random()</code> take any parameters?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It takes no parameters and returns a random <code>double</code> in the range [0.0, 1.0).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you generate a random integer in a specific range using <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>By scaling (multiplying) and shifting (adding). For example, <code>(int)(Math.random() * range) + min</code> produces an <code>int</code> from <code>min</code> to <code>min + range - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does "scaling" mean when manipulating <code>Math.random()</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p>Multiplying the result by a value to expand the range. For example, <code>Math.random() * 10</code> produces values from 0.0 to just under 10.0.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does "shifting" mean when manipulating <code>Math.random()</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p>Adding a value to move the range. For example, <code>Math.random() * 10 + 5</code> produces values from 5.0 to just under 15.0.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write an expression that produces a random integer from 1 to 6 (simulating a die roll).</p></front>
    <back><p><code>(int)(Math.random() * 6) + 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write an expression that produces a random <code>double</code> from 0.0 to just under 100.0.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Math.random() * 100</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What package is the <code>ArrayList</code> class in, and what must you do before using it?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList</code> is in the <code>java.util</code> package and must be imported before use.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you forget to import <code>ArrayList</code>, what kind of error will you get?</p></front>
    <back><p>A compile-time error, because the compiler cannot find the <code>ArrayList</code> class without importing <code>java.util.ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the import statement needed to use <code>ArrayList</code> in your program.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>ArrayList</code> part of the core <code>java.lang</code> package that is automatically available?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>ArrayList</code> is in <code>java.util</code>, which requires an explicit import.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does importing <code>ArrayList</code> differ from using <code>String</code> or <code>Math</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code> and <code>Math</code> are in <code>java.lang</code>, which is auto-imported. <code>ArrayList</code> is in <code>java.util</code> and must be explicitly imported.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Is an <code>ArrayList</code> object mutable or immutable?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> object is mutable; its contents can be changed after creation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does an <code>ArrayList</code> store primitive values or object references?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> contains object references, not primitive values.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that an <code>ArrayList</code> is mutable?</p></front>
    <back><p>You can add, remove, and change elements after the list is created, unlike immutable objects such as <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you store <code>int</code> values directly in an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>ArrayList</code> stores object references, so <code>int</code> values are autoboxed into <code>Integer</code> objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does the mutability of <code>ArrayList</code> compare to a Java array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both are mutable in that their elements can be changed, but <code>ArrayList</code> can also grow and shrink in size, while an array has a fixed length.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the no-argument <code>ArrayList</code> constructor create?</p></front>
    <back><p>It constructs an empty list with no elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the size of an <code>ArrayList</code> immediately after calling <code>new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>0, because the no-argument constructor creates an empty list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a statement that creates an empty <code>ArrayList</code> of <code>String</code> objects.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the no-argument <code>ArrayList</code> constructor accept an initial capacity?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The no-argument constructor takes no parameters and simply creates an empty list. A separate overloaded constructor accepts an initial capacity.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you pass initial elements to the no-argument <code>ArrayList</code> constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The no-argument constructor creates an empty list. You must add elements afterward using the <code>add</code> method.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the valid index range for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>size() - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If an <code>ArrayList</code> has 5 elements, what is the index of the last element?</p></front>
    <back><p>4, because indexes go from 0 to <code>size() - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the index of the first element in an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>0. <code>ArrayList</code> indexes start at 0, just like arrays.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>ArrayList</code> indexing compare to array indexing?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are the same: both start at 0 and end at one less than the number of elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>list.size()</code> returns 10, which indexes are valid for <code>list.get()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Indexes 0 through 9 (inclusive).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What exception is thrown when you access an invalid index in an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which <code>ArrayList</code> methods can throw an <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>get</code>, <code>set</code>, and <code>remove</code>, when called with an index outside the valid range.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you call <code>list.get(list.size())</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because the maximum valid index is <code>size() - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens when you call <code>list.get(-1)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because negative indexes are not valid.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> a compile-time error or a run-time error?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a run-time error (an unchecked exception thrown during program execution).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What exception is thrown if you add or remove elements from an <code>ArrayList</code> during an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ConcurrentModificationException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does modifying an <code>ArrayList</code> during an enhanced <code>for</code> loop cause an error?</p></front>
    <back><p>The enhanced <code>for</code> loop uses an internal iterator that detects structural changes and throws a <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> to prevent unpredictable behavior.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which operations should you avoid inside an enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Adding or removing elements, because changing the size of the list during traversal causes a <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you safely change an element's value (without adding or removing) inside an enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>You cannot use the enhanced <code>for</code> loop variable to set elements. You would need a regular <code>for</code> loop with <code>set()</code> to modify elements in place.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you need to remove elements while traversing an <code>ArrayList</code>, what should you use instead of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>A regular <code>for</code> loop (traversing carefully, often backwards) or an <code>Iterator</code> with its <code>remove()</code> method.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that <code>ArrayList</code> is a generic type?</p></front>
    <back><p>It means you can parameterize it with a specific element type, e.g. <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, so it only holds elements of that type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>E</code> represent in <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>E</code> is a type parameter that is replaced by a specific reference type, such as <code>String</code> or <code>Integer</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a declaration for an <code>ArrayList</code> that can only hold <code>Double</code> objects.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you create an <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Type parameters must be reference types, so you must use <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you try to add a <code>String</code> to an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The compiler produces an error because the type parameter restricts the list to <code>Integer</code> values only.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a "type parameter" in the context of <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A type parameter is a placeholder (like <code>E</code>) that is filled in with a specific reference type when the <code>ArrayList</code> is declared.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a type parameter be a primitive type?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Type parameters must be reference types, not primitives like <code>int</code> or <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't you use <code>boolean</code> as a type parameter for <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because type parameters must be reference types. You must use the wrapper class <code>Boolean</code> instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what is the type parameter filled in with?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>. Every <code>E</code> in the <code>ArrayList</code> API becomes <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between a type parameter and a method parameter?</p></front>
    <back><p>A type parameter specifies a type (filled in at compile time), while a method parameter specifies a value (filled in at run time).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>When <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> is specified with a type, what types do the <code>add</code> and <code>get</code> methods use?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>add</code> method accepts parameters of type <code>E</code>, and <code>get</code> returns values of type <code>E</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you have an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what type does <code>get(0)</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>, because <code>E</code> has been specified as <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>add(E obj)</code> when called on an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>boolean</code> (it always returns <code>true</code>). The parameter type becomes <code>Integer</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>, what type does the <code>set</code> method accept and return?</p></front>
    <back><p>It accepts a <code>Double</code> as the new value and returns the <code>Double</code> that was previously at that index.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is the type parameter useful for methods like <code>add</code> and <code>get</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It provides compile-time type safety: the compiler ensures only the correct type is added and the return type is known without casting.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> preferred over the raw type <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> allows the compiler to catch type errors at compile time that would otherwise only appear at run time.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a "raw" <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> declared without a type parameter, e.g. <code>ArrayList list = new ArrayList();</code>. It provides no compile-time type checking.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What kind of errors does using a raw <code>ArrayList</code> risk?</p></front>
    <back><p>Run-time errors such as <code>ClassCastException</code>, because the compiler cannot verify the types of elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you add both a <code>String</code> and an <code>Integer</code> to a raw <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It compiles without error, but you may get a <code>ClassCastException</code> at run time when you retrieve and cast elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the compiler generate a warning when you use a raw <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The compiler issues an "unchecked" warning to alert you that type safety is not guaranteed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is the diamond operator in <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The empty angle brackets <code>&lt;&gt;</code> tell the compiler to infer the element type from context, so you don't have to repeat it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can you write <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> instead of <code>new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The Java compiler infers the type parameter from the variable declaration on the left side of the assignment.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> equivalent to <code>ArrayList()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> uses the diamond operator for type inference (type-safe), while <code>ArrayList()</code> is a raw type (no type checking).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does the compiler infer from <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It infers that the constructor creates an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> based on the declared type on the left side.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When was the diamond operator (<code>&lt;&gt;</code>) introduced in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Java 7. Before that, you had to write the full type parameter on both sides of the declaration.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to "traverse" an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It means using iteration statements to access all the elements in the list, one at a time.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Name two types of loops that can be used to traverse an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>A regular <code>for</code> loop and an enhanced <code>for</code> (for-each) loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write an enhanced <code>for</code> loop that prints every element of <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; words</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (String w : words) { System.out.println(w); }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a regular <code>for</code> loop that prints every element of <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; words</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; words.size(); i++) { System.out.println(words.get(i)); }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When traversing an <code>ArrayList</code> with a regular <code>for</code> loop, what condition typically ends the loop?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>i &lt; list.size()</code>, since the last valid index is <code>size() - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are standard <code>ArrayList</code> algorithms that utilize traversals for?</p></front>
    <back><p>Inserting and deleting elements from an <code>ArrayList</code> while traversing it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why do insert/delete algorithms during traversal need special care?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because inserting or deleting shifts elements and changes the size, which can cause elements to be skipped or processed twice.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use an enhanced <code>for</code> loop for algorithms that insert or delete elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Modifying the list size during an enhanced <code>for</code> loop throws a <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What type of loop is typically used for insert/delete traversal algorithms on an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>A regular <code>for</code> loop, where you can manually adjust the index when elements shift.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is one common strategy for deleting elements during a forward traversal?</p></front>
    <back><p>Decrement the loop index after removing an element so the next element (which shifted left) is not skipped.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does deleting elements during a forward traversal of an <code>ArrayList</code> require special techniques?</p></front>
    <back><p>When an element is removed, subsequent elements shift left by one, so the next element moves into the current index and would be skipped if the index advances normally.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can you avoid skipping elements when removing from an <code>ArrayList</code> in a forward loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Decrement the loop variable after each removal, or traverse the list backwards.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does traversing backwards simplify deletion from an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Removing an element only shifts elements after the current index, which have already been processed, so no elements are skipped.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you remove index 2 from a 5-element list and then access index 2?</p></front>
    <back><p>You get the element that was formerly at index 3, because all elements after the removed one shift left by one position.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a backwards loop that removes all occurrences of <code>"x"</code> from <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; list</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>for (int i = list.size() - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) { if (list.get(i).equals("x")) list.remove(i); }</code></p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you convert an array algorithm to work with an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Replace <code>.length</code> with <code>.size()</code>, array accesses (<code>arr[i]</code>) with <code>get(i)</code>, and array assignments (<code>arr[i] = val</code>) with <code>set(i, val)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of <code>arr.length</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>list.size()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of <code>arr[i] = value</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>list.set(i, value)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of <code>arr[i]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>list.get(i)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What capability does <code>ArrayList</code> have that arrays do not, which may simplify some algorithms?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList</code> can dynamically grow and shrink with <code>add</code> and <code>remove</code>, whereas arrays have a fixed length.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean that some algorithms require traversing multiple structures simultaneously?</p></front>
    <back><p>The algorithm must walk through two or more <code>String</code>s, arrays, or <code>ArrayList</code>s at the same time, comparing or combining their elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of an algorithm that traverses two arrays simultaneously.</p></front>
    <back><p>Merging two sorted arrays into a single sorted array requires pointers (indexes) advancing through both arrays at the same time.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When traversing two <code>ArrayList</code>s of different sizes, what must you be careful about?</p></front>
    <back><p>You must handle the different sizes so you don't access an index beyond the smaller list's bounds.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How might you compare corresponding elements of two <code>ArrayList</code>s?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use a single <code>for</code> loop with the same index for both lists, iterating up to the smaller <code>size()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can an enhanced <code>for</code> loop easily traverse two <code>ArrayList</code>s simultaneously?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. An enhanced <code>for</code> loop only iterates over one collection at a time; you need a regular <code>for</code> loop with an index to traverse two structures together.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>int size()</code> return when called on an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The number of elements currently in the list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>size()</code> return on an empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>0.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>ArrayList.size()</code> differ from an array's <code>.length</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>size()</code> is a method call (with parentheses) that returns the current number of elements; <code>.length</code> is a field (no parentheses) that gives the array's fixed capacity.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After adding 3 elements and then removing 1 from an <code>ArrayList</code>, what does <code>size()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>2.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>size()</code> a field or a method?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a method. You call it with parentheses: <code>list.size()</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>boolean add(E obj)</code> do on an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It appends <code>obj</code> to the end of the list and returns <code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What value does <code>add(E obj)</code> always return?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>After calling <code>list.add("hello")</code>, where in the list is <code>"hello"</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>At the end of the list, at index <code>list.size() - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to the size of the <code>ArrayList</code> when you call <code>add(E obj)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>The size increases by one.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can <code>add(E obj)</code> ever return <code>false</code> for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. For <code>ArrayList</code>, <code>add</code> always returns <code>true</code>. (Some other <code>Collection</code> types can return <code>false</code>.)</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>void add(int index, E obj)</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It inserts <code>obj</code> at position <code>index</code>, shifting existing elements to the right and increasing the list size by one.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What values of <code>index</code> are valid for <code>add(int index, E obj)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Any value from <code>0</code> to <code>size()</code> inclusive. An index equal to <code>size()</code> appends to the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you call <code>add(list.size() + 1, obj)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because the index exceeds the current size.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>add(0, obj)</code> differ from <code>add(obj)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>add(0, obj)</code> inserts at the beginning of the list, shifting all elements right. <code>add(obj)</code> appends to the end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the two-argument <code>add</code> method return a value?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Its return type is <code>void</code>, unlike the one-argument <code>add</code> which returns <code>boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>E get(int index)</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It returns the element at position <code>index</code> in the list without modifying the list.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does <code>get</code> remove the element it returns?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>get</code> only returns the element; the list remains unchanged.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you call <code>get</code> with a negative index?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what is the return type of <code>get</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String</code>, because the type parameter <code>E</code> is <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>list.get(i)</code> similar to <code>arr[i]</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both retrieve the element at index <code>i</code>. The difference is syntax: method call vs. bracket notation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>E set(int index, E obj)</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It replaces the element at position <code>index</code> with <code>obj</code> and returns the element that was previously at that position.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>set</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The element that was formerly at the specified index.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does calling <code>set</code> change the size of the <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>set</code> replaces an existing element; the size stays the same.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you call <code>set</code> on an empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because there are no valid indexes.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>set(i, obj)</code> differ from <code>add(i, obj)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>set</code> replaces the element at index <code>i</code> (size unchanged). <code>add</code> inserts a new element at index <code>i</code>, shifting others right (size increases by 1).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>E remove(int index)</code> do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It removes the element at position <code>index</code>, shifts elements after it to the left, decreases the list size by one, and returns the removed element.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>remove</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The element that was formerly at the specified position.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to elements after the removed position when <code>remove</code> is called?</p></front>
    <back><p>They shift one position to the left (their indexes each decrease by one).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a list is <code>["a", "b", "c"]</code> and you call <code>remove(1)</code>, what is the list afterward?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>["a", "c"]</code>. <code>"b"</code> is removed and <code>"c"</code> shifts from index 2 to index 1.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does <code>remove</code> affect the value returned by <code>size()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>size()</code> decreases by one after each <code>remove</code> call.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the College Board emphasize wrapper classes?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because understanding wrapper classes is essential for using generics like <code>ArrayList</code>, which require reference types rather than primitives.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What would happen if wrapper classes didn't exist?</p></front>
    <back><p>You could not store primitive values in generic data structures like <code>ArrayList</code>, since generics require reference types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the emphasis on wrapper classes unique to the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>The AP exam places particular emphasis on them, though in practice autoboxing makes explicit use of wrapper classes relatively rare.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In modern Java, how often do you need to explicitly create wrapper objects?</p></front>
    <back><p>Rarely, because autoboxing handles conversion automatically. The main explicit use is in type parameters like <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which three wrapper classes does the AP exam focus on?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Why do the <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code> wrapper classes exist?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because generic types like <code>ArrayList</code> can only use reference types as type parameters, so wrapper classes wrap primitive values in objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What primitive type does <code>Integer</code> wrap?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What primitive type does <code>Double</code> wrap?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you use <code>int</code> directly as a type parameter for <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You must use the wrapper class <code>Integer</code>: <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to "wrap" a primitive value?</p></front>
    <back><p>It means enclosing the primitive in an object of the corresponding wrapper class so it can be used where a reference type is required.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is autoboxing in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive value to its corresponding wrapper type when used in a context requiring a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is unboxing in Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>Unboxing is the automatic conversion of a wrapper object to its corresponding primitive value when used in a context requiring a primitive.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of autoboxing in action.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); list.add(5);</code> — the <code>int</code> 5 is automatically boxed into an <code>Integer</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of unboxing in action.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int x = list.get(0);</code> — the <code>Integer</code> returned by <code>get</code> is automatically unboxed to an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need to write explicit wrapper constructors thanks to autoboxing?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The compiler handles the conversion automatically, so explicit wrapper construction is almost never needed.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Should you declare variables or parameters with wrapper types like <code>Integer</code> or <code>Double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Almost never. Use primitive types (<code>int</code>, <code>double</code>) and let autoboxing handle conversions when needed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When would you use a wrapper type as a method return type?</p></front>
    <back><p>Rarely. It is almost always better to return the primitive type and let Java autobox if needed.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is wrong with <code>Integer x = 5; Integer y = 10; Integer sum = x + y;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>It works due to autoboxing/unboxing, but it is unnecessarily using wrapper types. Better: <code>int x = 5; int y = 10; int sum = x + y;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why might using wrapper types for local variables hurt performance?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each wrapper object requires heap allocation and autoboxing/unboxing overhead, whereas primitives use the stack and are faster.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is it a good practice to write <code>Double average = 0.0;</code> instead of <code>double average = 0.0;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Use the primitive <code>double</code> for variables; only use <code>Double</code> in type parameters.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where must you use <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code> instead of <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>When declaring generic types like <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> or <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>, because type parameters require reference types.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why can't you write <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>int</code> is a primitive type and type parameters must be reference types. Use <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a declaration for an <code>ArrayList</code> of <code>boolean</code> values.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt; flags = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code> (you must use <code>Boolean</code>, not <code>boolean</code>).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between <code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt;</code> and <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt;</code> is invalid and won't compile. <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code> is correct because <code>Double</code> is a reference type.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can autoboxing help you avoid writing <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> as <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Autoboxing converts values, not types. The type parameter must still be <code>Integer</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>Integer(int value)</code> constructor do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It creates a new <code>Integer</code> object wrapping the specified <code>int</code> value. This is roughly equivalent to what autoboxing does.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the <code>Integer(int value)</code> constructor recommended in modern Java?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It has been deprecated since Java 9. Use <code>Integer.valueOf(int)</code> or rely on autoboxing instead.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the preferred alternative to <code>new Integer(42)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Integer.valueOf(42)</code>, which may reuse cached objects for better performance, or simply relying on autoboxing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>Integer.valueOf(int)</code> better than <code>new Integer(int)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>valueOf</code> caches frequently used values, yielding better space and time performance than always creating new objects.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between <code>new Integer(5)</code> and autoboxing?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both produce an <code>Integer</code> wrapping 5. Autoboxing is the compiler's automatic version of this conversion.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>intValue()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>int</code> primitive value stored inside the <code>Integer</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is <code>intValue()</code> called implicitly?</p></front>
    <back><p>During unboxing, when an <code>Integer</code> is used where an <code>int</code> is expected.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you typically need to call <code>intValue()</code> explicitly?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Java's unboxing handles this automatically in most situations.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the return type of <code>intValue()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>int</code> (the primitive type).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>Integer n = 42;</code>, what does <code>n.intValue()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The primitive <code>int</code> value <code>42</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>The maximum value that can be stored in an <code>int</code>: 2,147,483,647 (2^31 - 1).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> a method or a constant?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a <code>static final</code> constant (a field), not a method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you add 1 to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Integer overflow occurs, and the result wraps around to <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> (-2,147,483,648).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> useful in an algorithm?</p></front>
    <back><p>When initializing a variable to find the minimum value in a collection, you can start with <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> so any real value will be smaller.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the numeric value of <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>2,147,483,647 (approximately 2.1 billion).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> represent?</p></front>
    <back><p>The minimum value that can be stored in an <code>int</code>: -2,147,483,648 (-2^31).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> useful in an algorithm?</p></front>
    <back><p>When initializing a variable to find the maximum value in a collection, you can start with <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> so any real value will be larger.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> a method or a constant?</p></front>
    <back><p>It is a <code>static final</code> constant (a field), not a method.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> and <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> equals <code>-Integer.MAX_VALUE - 1</code> because two's complement representation has one more negative value than positive.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the numeric value of <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>-2,147,483,648.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the <code>Double(double value)</code> constructor do?</p></front>
    <back><p>It creates a new <code>Double</code> object wrapping the specified <code>double</code> value. This is equivalent to what autoboxing does.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the <code>Double(double value)</code> constructor recommended?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It has been deprecated since Java 9. Use <code>Double.valueOf(double)</code> or rely on autoboxing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is the <code>Double</code> constructor similar to the <code>Integer</code> constructor?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both wrap a primitive value in an object, both are deprecated since Java 9, and both are equivalent to autoboxing.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the preferred alternative to <code>new Double(3.14)</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Double.valueOf(3.14)</code> or simply relying on autoboxing: <code>Double d = 3.14;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the relationship between <code>new Double(2.5)</code> and autoboxing?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both produce a <code>Double</code> object containing 2.5. Autoboxing does this automatically when a <code>double</code> is used where <code>Double</code> is expected.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>doubleValue()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The <code>double</code> primitive value stored inside the <code>Double</code> object.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When is <code>doubleValue()</code> called implicitly?</p></front>
    <back><p>During unboxing, when a <code>Double</code> is used in a context expecting a <code>double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you typically need to call <code>doubleValue()</code> explicitly?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Java's unboxing handles the conversion automatically.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>doubleValue()</code> analogous to <code>intValue()</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both extract the primitive value from their wrapper object: <code>doubleValue()</code> returns a <code>double</code>, <code>intValue()</code> returns an <code>int</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If <code>Double d = 3.14;</code>, what does <code>d.doubleValue()</code> return?</p></front>
    <back><p>The primitive <code>double</code> value <code>3.14</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does the AP exam expect you to know any methods from the <code>Boolean</code> class?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. The College Board does not require knowledge of any <code>Boolean</code> class methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is <code>Boolean</code> listed as a wrapper class on the AP exam even though no methods are tested?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because you still need to use <code>Boolean</code> as a type parameter for <code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What wrapper class would you use for <code>ArrayList</code> of <code>boolean</code> values?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Boolean</code>, since <code>boolean</code> is a primitive and cannot be a type parameter.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which wrapper class on the AP Quick Reference has the fewest methods to memorize?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>Boolean</code>. The AP exam does not expect you to know any of its methods.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can autoboxing convert a <code>boolean</code> to a <code>Boolean</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Java autoboxes <code>boolean</code> to <code>Boolean</code> just like it does for <code>int</code>/<code>Integer</code> and <code>double</code>/<code>Double</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How can we informally compare algorithm efficiency?</p></front>
    <back><p>By counting statement executions, such as analyzing how many times a loop body runs.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is a more rigorous way to characterize algorithms beyond counting statements?</p></front>
    <back><p>By describing how the run time grows as the size of the problem grows (e.g., Big-O notation).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why might you analyze how many times a loop body executes?</p></front>
    <back><p>To estimate the algorithm's efficiency and compare it with alternative approaches.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does "how run time grows as the problem grows" describe?</p></front>
    <back><p>The algorithm's time complexity, which characterizes its scalability.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a loop runs N times and contains a nested loop that also runs N times, approximately how many statement executions occur?</p></front>
    <back><p>Approximately N squared (N x N) statement executions.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What statistics can standard algorithms compute from numbers in an array or <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Sum, average, minimum value, and maximum value.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>To find the minimum value in an array, what is a good initial value for your tracking variable?</p></front>
    <back><p>The first element of the array or <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you compute the average of values in an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Sum all elements, then divide by <code>size()</code>. Cast to <code>double</code> to avoid integer division.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the general pattern for finding the maximum value in a list?</p></front>
    <back><p>Initialize a variable to a very small value (or the first element), then traverse the list updating the variable whenever a larger value is found.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the same traversal compute both the minimum and maximum simultaneously?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Use two tracking variables and update each in the same loop body.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you determine if at least one element has a particular property?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse the collection and return <code>true</code> as soon as you find an element with the property. Return <code>false</code> after the loop ends without finding one.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the key difference between checking "at least one" vs. "all" elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>"At least one" returns <code>true</code> when the first match is found; "all" returns <code>false</code> when the first non-match is found.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Should you continue traversing after finding one element with the desired property in an "at least one" check?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You can return <code>true</code> immediately for efficiency.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write pseudocode to check if any element in an array is negative.</p></front>
    <back><p>Loop through each element; if element &lt; 0, return true. After the loop, return false.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should the method return if the array is empty and you are checking if at least one element has a property?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>false</code>, because there are no elements to satisfy the property.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you determine if all elements have a particular property?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse the collection and return <code>false</code> as soon as you find an element without the property. Return <code>true</code> after the loop completes.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should an "all elements" check return for an empty collection?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>true</code>, because there are no elements that violate the property (vacuous truth).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In an "all elements" check, when can you exit the loop early?</p></front>
    <back><p>As soon as you find any element that does not have the property.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does an "all elements" algorithm differ from an "at least one" algorithm structurally?</p></front>
    <back><p>In "all," you return <code>false</code> inside the loop on a mismatch and <code>true</code> after. In "at least one," you return <code>true</code> inside the loop on a match and <code>false</code> after.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write pseudocode to check if all elements in an array are positive.</p></front>
    <back><p>Loop through each element; if element &lt;= 0, return false. After the loop, return true.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to access all consecutive pairs of elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>Comparing or processing each element with the element immediately after it: (0,1), (1,2), (2,3), etc.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When iterating over consecutive pairs, what should the loop bound be?</p></front>
    <back><p>The loop should run from index 0 to <code>size() - 2</code> (or <code>length - 2</code>), accessing elements at <code>i</code> and <code>i + 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the consecutive pairs loop stop at <code>size() - 2</code> instead of <code>size() - 1</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because accessing <code>i + 1</code> when <code>i</code> equals <code>size() - 1</code> would be out of bounds.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example use case for accessing consecutive pairs.</p></front>
    <back><p>Checking if an array is sorted: compare each element with the next to verify they are in order.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many pairs are there in an array of N elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>N - 1 consecutive pairs.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you determine if an array or <code>ArrayList</code> contains duplicate elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use nested loops: for each element, compare it with every subsequent element. If a match is found, duplicates exist.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the typical time complexity of a brute-force duplicate detection algorithm?</p></front>
    <back><p>O(N squared), because it uses nested loops comparing each pair of elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a nested loop for duplicate detection, why should the inner loop start at <code>i + 1</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>To avoid comparing an element with itself and to avoid redundant comparisons of pairs already checked.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What would a duplicate detection algorithm return if the list is empty or has one element?</p></front>
    <back><p>No duplicates (return <code>false</code>), because there aren't enough elements to form a pair.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can duplicate detection be done more efficiently than nested loops?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, for example by sorting first (O(N log N)) or using a <code>HashSet</code> (O(N)), but the AP exam focuses on the nested loop approach.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you count elements meeting specific criteria in an array or <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Initialize a counter to 0, traverse the collection, and increment the counter each time an element meets the criteria.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should the counter variable be initialized to?</p></front>
    <back><p>0, before the traversal begins.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write pseudocode to count how many elements in an array are greater than 100.</p></front>
    <back><p>Set count = 0. Loop through each element; if element &gt; 100, increment count. Return count.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does counting elements differ from checking if at least one element meets criteria?</p></front>
    <back><p>Counting always traverses the entire collection and tracks a count; "at least one" can exit early as soon as a match is found.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is returned if no elements meet the criteria in a counting algorithm?</p></front>
    <back><p>0, the initial value of the counter.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does it mean to shift elements of an array left?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each element moves to the index one less than its current position. The first element is either lost or wrapped to the end (rotation).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between shifting and rotating elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>Shifting loses the element that falls off one end; rotating wraps that element around to the other end.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When shifting elements right, which end of the array do you start copying from?</p></front>
    <back><p>The right end (highest index), working leftward, to avoid overwriting elements before they are copied.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When shifting elements left, which end do you start from?</p></front>
    <back><p>The left end (lowest index), working rightward, copying each element from <code>i + 1</code> to <code>i</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If you rotate <code>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</code> one position to the left, what is the result?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>[2, 3, 4, 5, 1]</code>. The first element wraps around to the end.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you reverse the order of elements in an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Swap elements from the outside in: swap index 0 with the last index, index 1 with the second-to-last, and so on until the middle is reached.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How many swaps are needed to reverse an array of N elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>N / 2 swaps (integer division).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if you iterate through the entire array swapping without stopping at the middle?</p></front>
    <back><p>Each element gets swapped twice, returning the array to its original order.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write the loop condition for reversing an array using two pointers <code>left</code> and <code>right</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>while (left &lt; right)</code> — stop when the pointers meet or cross.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the same reversal algorithm work for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, using <code>get</code> and <code>set</code> instead of array bracket notation, with the same two-pointer approach.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does a frequency algorithm determine?</p></front>
    <back><p>How often a specific criterion is met by elements within an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does a frequency algorithm differ from a counting algorithm?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are essentially the same: both count how many elements meet a given criterion. "Frequency" emphasizes the rate or proportion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you find the most frequent element in an array?</p></front>
    <back><p>Count the frequency of each element (e.g., using nested loops) and track which element has the highest count.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between counting elements and determining frequency?</p></front>
    <back><p>Counting gives the raw number; frequency can also refer to the proportion of elements meeting the criterion relative to the total count.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write pseudocode to find the frequency of value <code>x</code> in an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p>Set count = 0. For each element in the list, if element equals x, increment count. Return count.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you identify the individual digits of an integer?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use <code>% 10</code> to get the last digit and <code>/ 10</code> to remove the last digit, repeating until the number is 0.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>n % 10</code> give you?</p></front>
    <back><p>The last (ones) digit of <code>n</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does <code>n / 10</code> do (integer division)?</p></front>
    <back><p>Removes the last digit from <code>n</code>, shifting all other digits one place to the right.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In what order are digits extracted using the <code>% 10</code> and <code>/ 10</code> technique?</p></front>
    <back><p>Right to left (least significant digit first).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you sum the digits of the number 1234?</p></front>
    <back><p>Repeatedly take <code>n % 10</code> (getting 4, 3, 2, 1) and add each to a running sum, dividing <code>n</code> by 10 each iteration. Result: 10.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a standard <code>String</code> traversal algorithm for finding substrings with a property?</p></front>
    <back><p>Use a loop with <code>substring()</code> to extract each substring and check whether it has the desired property.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do you traverse all single characters of a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Loop from index 0 to <code>length() - 1</code>, using <code>charAt(i)</code> or <code>substring(i, i+1)</code> to access each character.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you check if a <code>String</code> contains a substring of all vowels?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse all possible substrings and check if each consists entirely of vowels.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What method extracts a portion of a <code>String</code> for examination?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>substring(beginIndex, endIndex)</code>, which returns the characters from <code>beginIndex</code> to <code>endIndex - 1</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you modify characters in a <code>String</code> during traversal?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. <code>String</code> objects are immutable. You must build a new <code>String</code> with the desired changes.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you count substrings that meet specific criteria?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse the <code>String</code>, extract each relevant substring, check the criterion, and increment a counter when it is met.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you count the number of uppercase letters in a <code>String</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse each character and count those where <code>Character.isUpperCase(ch)</code> returns true.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the general pattern for counting substrings meeting a criterion?</p></front>
    <back><p>Initialize counter to 0, loop through positions, extract substring, test criterion, increment counter if met.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How would you count occurrences of <code>"ab"</code> in the string <code>"ababab"</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>Loop from 0 to <code>length() - 2</code>, check if <code>substring(i, i+2).equals("ab")</code>, and count matches. Result: 3.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the counting algorithm need to handle overlapping substrings?</p></front>
    <back><p>It depends on the problem. A simple loop checking each starting position will count overlapping occurrences naturally.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do you create a new <code>String</code> with its characters reversed?</p></front>
    <back><p>Traverse the original <code>String</code> from the last character to the first, appending each character to a new <code>String</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why must you create a new <code>String</code> when reversing, rather than modifying the original?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because <code>String</code> objects are immutable in Java; their characters cannot be changed after creation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Write a loop that builds a reversed version of <code>String s</code>.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>String rev = ""; for (int i = s.length() - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) { rev += s.charAt(i); }</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is an alternative approach to reversing a <code>String</code> without looping backwards?</p></front>
    <back><p>Loop forward and prepend each character: <code>rev = s.charAt(i) + rev;</code></p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can a reversed <code>String</code> be used to check for palindromes?</p></front>
    <back><p>Reverse the <code>String</code> and compare it to the original using <code>.equals()</code>. If they are equal, it is a palindrome.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a sequential (linear) search?</p></front>
    <back><p>An algorithm that checks each element in order from beginning to end until the desired value is found or all elements have been checked.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does a linear search require the data to be sorted?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Linear search works on both sorted and unsorted data.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the worst-case number of comparisons for a linear search on N elements?</p></front>
    <back><p>N comparisons (the element is last or not present).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Should you be able to write a linear search for the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. You should be able to write code that performs a linear search on an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What does a linear search return if the element is not found?</p></front>
    <back><p>Typically -1 (or some sentinel value) to indicate the element was not found in the collection.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How much more efficient is binary search compared to linear search?</p></front>
    <back><p>Binary search finds elements in log N time, compared to linear search's N time, making it much faster for large sorted lists.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What precondition must be met for binary search to work?</p></front>
    <back><p>The data must be sorted.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a sorted list has 1,000,000 elements, approximately how many comparisons does binary search need?</p></front>
    <back><p>About 20 (log base 2 of 1,000,000 is approximately 20).</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Are you likely to have to write a binary search on the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You are unlikely to need to write one yourself, but you should understand how it works.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is binary search impractical for unsorted data?</p></front>
    <back><p>Binary search eliminates half the data based on comparisons with the middle element, which only works correctly if the data is in sorted order.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Where does the binary search algorithm start?</p></front>
    <back><p>At the middle element of the sorted array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What fraction of elements does binary search eliminate in each iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>On average, half of the remaining elements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if the middle element equals the target in binary search?</p></front>
    <back><p>The search is complete; the target has been found at that index.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If the target is less than the middle element in binary search, which half do you search next?</p></front>
    <back><p>The left half (elements before the middle), since the array is sorted in ascending order.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>When does binary search conclude that the target is not in the list?</p></front>
    <back><p>When all elements have been eliminated (the search range is empty).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can binary search be implemented both iteratively and recursively?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. The binary search algorithm can be written either way.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What changes between iterative and recursive binary search?</p></front>
    <back><p>The iterative version uses a loop with low/high pointers; the recursive version passes updated low/high bounds as parameters to recursive calls.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In a recursive binary search, what is the base case?</p></front>
    <back><p>When the search range is empty (low &gt; high) meaning the element is not found, or when the middle element equals the target.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In an iterative binary search, what is the loop condition?</p></front>
    <back><p>Typically <code>while (low &lt;= high)</code>, continuing as long as there are elements left to search.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Which version of binary search (iterative or recursive) is more common on the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both may appear. You should be able to trace through either version, though you are unlikely to have to write one yourself.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What are selection sort and insertion sort?</p></front>
    <back><p>Iterative sorting algorithms that can sort elements in an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need to be able to write selection sort or insertion sort for the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You should be able to recognize them but will not have to write them yourself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does selection sort work conceptually?</p></front>
    <back><p>It repeatedly finds the minimum element from the unsorted portion and swaps it into the next position in the sorted portion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does insertion sort work conceptually?</p></front>
    <back><p>It builds the sorted portion one element at a time, inserting each new element into its correct position within the already-sorted portion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What type of algorithm are selection sort and insertion sort: iterative or recursive?</p></front>
    <back><p>Iterative. They use loops rather than recursion.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is merge sort?</p></front>
    <back><p>A recursive sorting algorithm that divides the data in half, sorts each half, and merges the sorted halves back together.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Do you need to be able to write merge sort for the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. You will not have to write a merge sort.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How does merge sort differ from selection sort and insertion sort?</p></front>
    <back><p>Merge sort is recursive and divides the problem in half each time; selection and insertion sort are iterative.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the key operation in merge sort?</p></front>
    <back><p>Merging two already-sorted halves into a single sorted sequence.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the time complexity of merge sort compared to selection and insertion sort?</p></front>
    <back><p>Merge sort is O(N log N), while selection and insertion sort are O(N squared).</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is a recursive method?</p></front>
    <back><p>A method that calls itself.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the difference between direct and mutual recursion?</p></front>
    <back><p>Direct recursion is when a method calls itself. Mutual recursion is when method A calls method B, which calls method A. The AP exam focuses on direct recursion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Does the AP curriculum cover mutual recursion?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. It focuses only on simple one-method (direct) recursion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a method be recursive if it never directly calls itself?</p></front>
    <back><p>Technically yes, through mutual recursion (A calls B, B calls A), but the AP curriculum only considers direct self-calls as recursion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give a simple example of a recursive method signature.</p></front>
    <back><p><code>public int factorial(int n)</code> — where the body includes a call to <code>factorial(n - 1)</code>.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What two things must every recursive method contain?</p></front>
    <back><p>At least one base case (which halts the recursion) and at least one recursive call.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if a recursive method has no base case?</p></front>
    <back><p>It will recurse infinitely and eventually cause a <code>StackOverflowError</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is the purpose of the base case in recursion?</p></front>
    <back><p>To stop the recursion by providing a direct answer without making another recursive call.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a recursive method have more than one base case?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. A method can have multiple base cases for different stopping conditions.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a recursive method have more than one recursive call?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. For example, tree recursion (like computing Fibonacci numbers) makes two recursive calls per invocation.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Does each recursive call get its own set of local variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Each call has its own independent set of local variables, including its parameters.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>If a recursive method has a local variable <code>x</code>, do all active calls share the same <code>x</code>?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Each call has its own copy of <code>x</code> stored in its own stack frame.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Where are the local variables for each recursive call stored?</p></front>
    <back><p>On the call stack, in separate stack frames for each active method invocation.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens to a recursive call's local variables when that call returns?</p></front>
    <back><p>They are removed from the stack, and execution resumes in the calling method with its own local variables.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it important that each recursive call has independent local variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>It allows each level of recursion to track its own state without interfering with other levels.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>How do parameter values in recursion relate to loop control variables?</p></front>
    <back><p>Parameter values capture the progress of a recursive process, much like loop control variables capture the progress of a loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>In <code>factorial(n)</code>, what role does <code>n</code> play analogous to a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p><code>n</code> tracks progress toward the base case, similar to how a loop variable counts toward a termination condition.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What happens if the parameters in recursive calls don't change toward the base case?</p></front>
    <back><p>The recursion never reaches the base case, resulting in infinite recursion and a <code>StackOverflowError</code>.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How is <code>countdown(n-1)</code> in a recursive method similar to <code>i--</code> in a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Both move closer to a stopping condition: the recursive parameter approaches the base case, and the loop variable approaches the loop bound.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why must recursive calls change the parameter values?</p></front>
    <back><p>To make progress toward the base case and ensure the recursion eventually terminates.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What structures can recursion be used to traverse?</p></front>
    <back><p>Linear structures like <code>String</code>s, arrays, and <code>ArrayList</code>s, as well as tree structures.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>For which type of structure is recursion most useful?</p></front>
    <back><p>Tree structures, which are difficult to traverse with simple loops.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is recursion particularly suited for tree structures?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because trees branch, and recursion naturally handles branching by making separate recursive calls for each branch.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can you traverse an array using recursion instead of a loop?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes, but a loop is usually simpler and more natural for linear traversals.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a tree structure that benefits from recursive traversal.</p></front>
    <back><p>A file system directory tree, a binary search tree, or a recursively defined data structure like nested lists.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>Can any recursive solution be rewritten iteratively?</p></front>
    <back><p>Yes. Any recursive solution can be replicated using an iterative approach.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What extra requirement does converting tree recursion to iteration involve?</p></front>
    <back><p>Maintaining extra data structures (like a stack) to keep track of information that would otherwise be managed by the recursion.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is converting tree recursion to iteration more complex than converting linear recursion?</p></front>
    <back><p>Tree recursion branches into multiple calls, so you need an explicit stack or queue to track the multiple paths, whereas linear recursion maps directly to a simple loop.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What data structure typically replaces the call stack when converting recursion to iteration?</p></front>
    <back><p>An explicit <code>Stack</code> (or sometimes a <code>Queue</code>) that stores the state that would have been in each recursive call's stack frame.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Is the iterative version of an algorithm always preferred over the recursive version?</p></front>
    <back><p>Not necessarily. Recursive solutions can be clearer and more natural for problems with recursive structure, such as tree traversals.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What does the AP exam say about system reliability?</p></front>
    <back><p>System reliability is limited, and programmers should make an effort to maximize it.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is system reliability considered limited?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because software and hardware can have bugs, failures, and unexpected conditions that prevent perfect reliability.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should programmers do about system reliability?</p></front>
    <back><p>Make an effort to maximize it through testing, error handling, and robust design.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of how a programmer can improve system reliability.</p></front>
    <back><p>By writing thorough tests, handling edge cases, validating input, and implementing error recovery mechanisms.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can a system ever be made 100% reliable?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. System reliability is inherently limited, but programmers should strive to maximize it.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What concerns arise regarding legal issues when creating programs?</p></front>
    <back><p>Legal issues and intellectual property concerns, such as copyright, licensing, and patents.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What is intellectual property in the context of programming?</p></front>
    <back><p>Creations of the mind (code, algorithms, designs) that may be legally protected through copyright, patents, or licenses.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why should programmers be aware of intellectual property?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because using someone else's code or ideas without permission can violate copyright or licensing agreements.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a legal issue a programmer might face.</p></front>
    <back><p>Using open-source code with a restrictive license in a proprietary product without complying with the license terms.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How do legal issues relate to the AP exam?</p></front>
    <back><p>The AP exam expects awareness that creating programs raises legal and intellectual property concerns, though deep legal knowledge is not tested.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What kinds of impacts can the creation of programs have?</p></front>
    <back><p>Impacts on society, economies, and culture, which can be both beneficial and harmful.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Can the societal impacts of programs be only positive?</p></front>
    <back><p>No. Impacts can be both beneficial and harmful.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a beneficial impact of a program on society.</p></front>
    <back><p>Medical software that helps diagnose diseases, communication tools that connect people globally, or educational platforms.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of a harmful impact of a program on society.</p></front>
    <back><p>Social media algorithms that spread misinformation, software that enables surveillance, or automation that displaces workers.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why is it important for programmers to consider the societal impacts of their work?</p></front>
    <back><p>Because programs can affect large numbers of people and have lasting consequences on society, economies, and culture.</p></back>
  </card>

  <card>
    <front><p>What is at risk when using a computer, according to the AP curriculum?</p></front>
    <back><p>Personal privacy.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>What should programmers do about personal privacy?</p></front>
    <back><p>Attempt to safeguard it when designing and building software.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Give an example of how a program might put personal privacy at risk.</p></front>
    <back><p>Collecting more user data than necessary, storing passwords in plain text, or sharing user information with third parties without consent.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>How can a programmer safeguard personal privacy?</p></front>
    <back><p>By encrypting sensitive data, minimizing data collection, implementing access controls, and following privacy regulations.</p></back>
  </card>
  <card>
    <front><p>Why does the AP exam include personal privacy as a topic?</p></front>
    <back><p>To ensure students understand that software development carries ethical responsibilities, including protecting users' private information.</p></back>
  </card>

</deck>
